WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:07.600
[Amit Varma]: How should we think of medicine as a profession?

00:00:07.600 --> 00:00:10.120
[Amit Varma]: On the one hand, it's a career path like any other.

00:00:10.120 --> 00:00:13.400
[Amit Varma]: You learn a skill, and people pay you for your expertise.

00:00:13.400 --> 00:00:16.400
[Amit Varma]: But on the other hand, it's also thought of as a noble calling.

00:00:16.400 --> 00:00:17.740
[Amit Varma]: You help other people.

00:00:17.740 --> 00:00:21.640
[Amit Varma]: You sometimes give them the gift of life, and sometimes you give them a better life.

00:00:21.640 --> 00:00:27.160
[Amit Varma]: In India, doctors are mostly invisible to us, except when we have no option but to notice

00:00:27.160 --> 00:00:28.160
[Amit Varma]: them.

00:00:28.160 --> 00:00:30.200
[Amit Varma]: Doctors can be both villains and heroes to us.

00:00:30.200 --> 00:00:34.920
[Amit Varma]: On one hand, we rail against doctors who over-prescribe tests and medicine because that's the way

00:00:34.920 --> 00:00:37.120
[Amit Varma]: their incentives go and patients be damned.

00:00:37.120 --> 00:00:38.920
[Amit Varma]: We are objects to them.

00:00:38.920 --> 00:00:43.560
[Amit Varma]: On the other hand, we go to them with our deepest problems, including our greatest anxiety,

00:00:43.560 --> 00:00:44.560
[Amit Varma]: the fear of death.

00:00:44.560 --> 00:00:48.680
[Amit Varma]: And I'm not being hyperbolic when I say that over the last year, doctors and nurses

00:00:48.680 --> 00:00:52.480
[Amit Varma]: and other medical personnel have been our greatest heroes.

00:00:52.480 --> 00:00:56.980
[Amit Varma]: Lakhs of these frontline workers in India have gone beyond their call of duty, functioning

00:00:56.980 --> 00:01:01.400
[Amit Varma]: in a battleground with limited information, driven not just by money, but by empathy and

00:01:01.400 --> 00:01:03.400
[Amit Varma]: the desperate desire to help.

00:01:03.400 --> 00:01:06.200
[Amit Varma]: They have risked their lives to save the lives of others.

00:01:06.200 --> 00:01:10.520
[Amit Varma]: When I think of those who let us down in this crisis, and the politicians are on top of

00:01:10.520 --> 00:01:13.540
[Amit Varma]: that list, I begin to lose faith in humanity.

00:01:13.540 --> 00:01:17.240
[Amit Varma]: But then I look at the medical profession and I regain that faith.

00:01:17.240 --> 00:01:19.260
[Amit Varma]: You see, we will beat this pandemic.

00:01:19.260 --> 00:01:22.760
[Amit Varma]: And it won't just be a triumph of science and medicine when we do.

00:01:22.760 --> 00:01:29.840
[Unknown]: It will also be a triumph of human beings expressing their humanity.

00:01:29.840 --> 00:01:32.320
[Unknown]: Welcome to the scene and the unseen.

00:01:32.320 --> 00:01:36.400
[Unknown]: Our weekly podcast on economics, politics and behavioral science.

00:01:36.400 --> 00:01:42.440
[Amit Varma]: Please welcome your host, Amit Verma.

00:01:42.440 --> 00:01:43.720
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to the scene and the unseen.

00:01:43.720 --> 00:01:48.540
[Amit Varma]: My guest today is Lancelot Pinto, a doctor and a scholar who has come to public attention

00:01:48.540 --> 00:01:53.440
[Amit Varma]: in the last few months for being a voice of reason in this fog of confusion.

00:01:53.440 --> 00:01:58.400
[Amit Varma]: Lance has been clearing doubts and misconceptions since this pandemic began and has been especially

00:01:58.400 --> 00:02:04.400
[Amit Varma]: eloquent in recent weeks on the dangers of over-prescribing drugs to COVID patients.

00:02:04.400 --> 00:02:07.960
[Amit Varma]: Many of the deaths in recent weeks have come because of a dysfunctional state and were

00:02:07.960 --> 00:02:09.520
[Amit Varma]: otherwise avoidable.

00:02:09.520 --> 00:02:14.800
[Amit Varma]: But some have happened because of over-medication of doctors going overboard with medicine that

00:02:14.800 --> 00:02:16.960
[Amit Varma]: has adverse side effects.

00:02:16.960 --> 00:02:21.440
[Amit Varma]: Lance called this out early and I wouldn't be surprised if he saved lives not just in

00:02:21.440 --> 00:02:26.920
[Amit Varma]: his work as a doctor, but also in his interventions as a public intellectual.

00:02:26.920 --> 00:02:31.000
[Amit Varma]: Friends of mine have actually been patients of his in this time and praise him highly.

00:02:31.000 --> 00:02:33.720
[Amit Varma]: I was delighted when he agreed to be a guest on the show.

00:02:33.720 --> 00:02:37.000
[Amit Varma]: I wanted to explore a much wider canvas than just COVID though.

00:02:37.000 --> 00:02:39.840
[Amit Varma]: I wanted to explore the practice of medicine.

00:02:39.840 --> 00:02:42.160
[Amit Varma]: Why do doctors opt for this profession?

00:02:42.160 --> 00:02:46.320
[Amit Varma]: What is a doctor's life really like away from the glamour of Robin Cook novels and

00:02:46.320 --> 00:02:48.160
[Amit Varma]: ER and scrubs?

00:02:48.160 --> 00:02:52.840
[Amit Varma]: What are the incentives that drive doctors, both as doctors and as human beings?

00:02:52.840 --> 00:02:56.520
[Amit Varma]: How do they stay in touch with the cutting edge of medicine, which may be so different

00:02:56.520 --> 00:02:59.160
[Amit Varma]: from what they learnt in their college textbooks?

00:02:59.160 --> 00:03:04.800
[Amit Varma]: Beyond these general questions, I also wanted to talk about some of Lance's areas of specialisation.

00:03:04.800 --> 00:03:09.840
[Amit Varma]: He runs smoking cessation clinics and talks about how medicine has now made it easy to

00:03:09.840 --> 00:03:10.880
[Amit Varma]: quit smoking.

00:03:10.880 --> 00:03:16.760
[Amit Varma]: He talks about the importance of sleep and the unintuitive ways in which our body functions.

00:03:16.760 --> 00:03:21.000
[Amit Varma]: Did you know that a throat muscle can cause erectile dysfunction?

00:03:21.000 --> 00:03:23.280
[Amit Varma]: This is the scene and the unseen right there.

00:03:23.280 --> 00:03:27.880
[Amit Varma]: So we cover a lot of ground in this episode, and only the last half an hour or so is actually

00:03:27.880 --> 00:03:28.880
[Amit Varma]: about COVID-19.

