00:05:36.040 --> 00:05:36.800
[Amit Varma]: So Amit, tell me about your childhood.

00:05:36.800 --> 00:05:37.840
[Amit Varma]: Where did you grow up?

00:05:37.840 --> 00:05:40.840
[Amit Varma]: What was it like before your journey in medicine began?

00:05:40.840 --> 00:05:45.480
[Guest]: To begin with, Amit I don't think you've missed anything much in terms of my journey.

00:05:45.480 --> 00:05:46.880
[Guest]: But I grew up in Mumbai.

00:05:46.880 --> 00:05:50.240
[Guest]: I was born in Mumbai, grew up here, born in Bombay, grew up in Mumbai.

00:05:50.240 --> 00:05:51.560
[Guest]: That's how I like to say it.

00:05:51.560 --> 00:05:55.440
[Guest]: I was born in the suburbs of Mumbai called Bhandup.

00:05:55.440 --> 00:05:58.160
[Guest]: It's a small little suburb on the central line.

00:05:58.160 --> 00:06:03.240
[Guest]: So if you're familiar with Bombay, the suburbs are looked down upon very often but that's

00:06:03.240 --> 00:06:04.420
[Guest]: where I began.

00:06:04.420 --> 00:06:10.720
[Guest]: I went to a school called St. Xavier's School and my dad worked in administration at Crompton

00:06:10.720 --> 00:06:17.200
[Guest]: Greaves and pretty much held one job all his life, you know, so that was who he was.

00:06:17.200 --> 00:06:19.640
[Guest]: My mother was a school teacher at the school that I studied in.

00:06:19.640 --> 00:06:22.000
[Guest]: She was a primary school teacher.

00:06:22.000 --> 00:06:26.720
[Guest]: And both of them were migrants from Mangalore, so they moved after they got married.

00:06:26.720 --> 00:06:29.920
[Guest]: My dad was here for a couple of years before that.

00:06:29.920 --> 00:06:33.360
[Guest]: And you know, I remember my dad telling me stories about how he came to the city with

00:06:33.360 --> 00:06:37.280
[Guest]: nothing, which is so true for a lot of migrants to Mumbai.

00:06:37.280 --> 00:06:40.960
[Guest]: He stayed with his brother, who was already here for some time.

00:06:40.960 --> 00:06:43.160
[Guest]: And that was my childhood.

00:06:43.160 --> 00:06:46.240
[Guest]: So I grew up in a family where both my parents worked.

00:06:46.240 --> 00:06:50.280
[Guest]: I think there was a strong ethos on working hard.

00:06:50.280 --> 00:06:54.120
[Guest]: You know, I remember my dad leaving home at seven in the morning because he worked in

00:06:54.120 --> 00:06:58.920
[Guest]: South Bombay, which is the other end of town, and would return by 7.30 or so in the evening.

00:06:58.920 --> 00:07:00.960
[Guest]: I think education was always very important.

00:07:00.960 --> 00:07:02.440
[Guest]: There was a stress on education.

00:07:02.440 --> 00:07:04.040
[Guest]: However, I never felt pressured.

00:07:04.040 --> 00:07:09.000
[Guest]: There was never any pressure to perform or, you know, there was never any, you will grow

00:07:09.000 --> 00:07:13.360
[Guest]: up and become a doctor or engineer or anything of that sort.

00:07:13.360 --> 00:07:17.000
[Guest]: Fortunately for me, and I really don't know, I mean, there may be a lot of subtle things

00:07:17.000 --> 00:07:19.720
[Guest]: that help in life, which you don't realize.

00:07:19.720 --> 00:07:21.720
[Guest]: Fortunately for me, I think I liked studying.

00:07:21.720 --> 00:07:23.000
[Guest]: I was happy going to school.

00:07:23.000 --> 00:07:26.680
[Guest]: I, in fact, you know, at the end of vacations, I was looking forward to school beginning

00:07:26.680 --> 00:07:27.680
[Guest]: again.

00:07:27.680 --> 00:07:34.280
[Guest]: And I was naturally drawn towards reading and studying and fortunately did well.

00:07:34.280 --> 00:07:38.120
[Guest]: Somewhere along, you know, when you reach middle school to high school is when you start

00:07:38.120 --> 00:07:40.280
[Guest]: thinking about what you want to become.

00:07:40.280 --> 00:07:42.680
[Guest]: And I think I always wanted to become a pilot for some time.

00:07:42.680 --> 00:07:47.960
[Guest]: Again, I guess it's a common thing for a lot of people to want to do adventurous things

00:07:47.960 --> 00:07:48.960
[Guest]: like that.

00:07:48.960 --> 00:07:52.960
[Guest]: But I think at some point of time, somewhere close to maybe my seventh grade or so, this

00:07:52.960 --> 00:07:56.040
[Guest]: whole thing about taking up medicine became real.

00:07:56.040 --> 00:08:01.000
[Guest]: Maybe it was influenced by the fact that my dad had a bypass when I was in the sixth standard.

00:08:01.000 --> 00:08:03.800
[Guest]: There was some interaction with the healthcare system.

00:08:03.800 --> 00:08:07.960
[Guest]: Maybe I looked up to some of those doctors in awe and there was a lot of reading of Robin

00:08:07.960 --> 00:08:11.520
[Guest]: Cook as well, which I don't know whether that's a good thing or a bad thing, because that's

00:08:11.520 --> 00:08:15.240
[Guest]: a very skewed presentation of medicine, but it still looks glamorous.

00:08:15.240 --> 00:08:16.240
[Guest]: It looks interesting.

00:08:16.240 --> 00:08:18.920
[Guest]: And I think I was naturally drawn towards medicine at that point of time.

00:08:18.920 --> 00:08:22.320
[Guest]: So somewhere around the seventh or eighth standard, it was medicine and nothing else

00:08:22.320 --> 00:08:23.320
[Guest]: for me.

00:08:23.320 --> 00:08:29.240
[Guest]: Of course, growing up in a middle-class household in Mumbai, you do not think of too many different

00:08:29.240 --> 00:08:30.240
[Guest]: options as a career.

00:08:30.240 --> 00:08:33.600
[Guest]: You think of medicine, you think of engineering, you think of a few other things.

00:08:33.600 --> 00:08:38.640
[Guest]: And in hindsight, maybe my alternative life would also include the possibility of journalism,

00:08:38.640 --> 00:08:43.360
[Guest]: the possibility of being an author, the possibility of exploring the humanities in some way, because

00:08:43.360 --> 00:08:48.080
[Guest]: I think that's a big lacuna in medical education that we aren't exposed to humanities.

00:08:48.080 --> 00:08:54.080
[Guest]: So 10th standard, you know, big year, important year, you have to do well, I did reasonably

00:08:54.080 --> 00:08:55.080
[Guest]: okay.

00:08:55.080 --> 00:09:00.280
[Guest]: I went to a college called RUIA, which was, so that's another recurring theme in my life.

00:09:00.280 --> 00:09:04.440
[Guest]: I always got into the second best college, I think, or second best of mostly everything.

00:09:04.440 --> 00:09:05.440
[Guest]: And we talk about that.

00:09:05.440 --> 00:09:08.600
[Guest]: So, you know, the number one college in Mumbai was considered Rupert L for the sciences.

00:09:08.600 --> 00:09:09.600
[Guest]: I didn't make the cut.

00:09:09.600 --> 00:09:11.680
[Guest]: So I went to RUIA.

00:09:11.680 --> 00:09:16.600
[Guest]: Then 12th standard is another, you know, you realize that it's from a pool of 10,000 odd

00:09:16.600 --> 00:09:21.960
[Guest]: people, about 100 seats are what's available in the public institutions where you want

00:09:21.960 --> 00:09:25.040
[Guest]: to be in terms of an MBBS education.

00:09:25.040 --> 00:09:28.520
[Guest]: And again, you know, the King Edward Memorial Hospital, or KEM is considered number one

00:09:28.520 --> 00:09:29.520
[Guest]: in Mumbai.

00:09:29.520 --> 00:09:30.520
[Guest]: I didn't.

00:09:30.520 --> 00:09:32.360
[Guest]: So my percentage was 95.

00:09:32.360 --> 00:09:35.560
[Guest]: And I think KEM stopped at 95 point something.

00:09:35.560 --> 00:09:38.280
[Guest]: So I got into Sion Hospital.

00:09:38.280 --> 00:09:43.720
[Guest]: And Sion Hospital was a very interesting experience in terms of, you know, there was a decent

00:09:43.720 --> 00:09:49.400
[Guest]: balance of extracurricular activities as well as studies where, you know, it wasn't the

00:09:49.400 --> 00:09:53.560
[Guest]: typical nerds where everybody constantly had their heads buried in books.

00:09:53.560 --> 00:09:56.480
[Guest]: We had this festival called Ashwamedh, which was quite important every year.

00:09:56.480 --> 00:10:02.800
[Guest]: So we got some exposure to, you know, debating, to doing a lot of public speaking, etc.

00:10:02.800 --> 00:10:04.720
[Guest]: And those were good years.

00:10:04.720 --> 00:10:07.360
[Guest]: That's pretty much the early years, if you ask me.

00:10:07.360 --> 00:10:11.060
[Amit Varma]: So you know, what kind of strikes me was that growing up as an 80s kid, I remember back

00:10:11.060 --> 00:10:15.320
[Amit Varma]: in the day, the traditional occupations that good middle class kids were supposed to go

00:10:15.320 --> 00:10:20.760
[Amit Varma]: as you said, was you do doctor and engineering, and a little later on MBA also became kind

00:10:20.760 --> 00:10:21.760
[Amit Varma]: of fashionable.

00:10:21.760 --> 00:10:23.760
[Amit Varma]: And this, of course, is if you didn't sit for the civil services.

00:10:23.760 --> 00:10:29.240
[Amit Varma]: Now, I would imagine that by the 90s, post liberalization, all of this is kind of changing.

00:10:29.240 --> 00:10:33.400
[Amit Varma]: But nevertheless, I think in the second half of the 90s, you decide to go in for an MBBS

00:10:33.400 --> 00:10:36.640
[Amit Varma]: anyway, and you pointed out that you had a natural interest in this.

00:10:36.640 --> 00:10:38.060
[Amit Varma]: So a couple of things strike me.

00:10:38.060 --> 00:10:42.480
[Amit Varma]: One is that it takes an awfully long time to become a doctor, you do your engineering

00:10:42.480 --> 00:10:44.120
[Amit Varma]: course and you're an engineer.

00:10:44.120 --> 00:10:48.080
[Amit Varma]: But with a doctor, it's just a years keep stretching on, it almost seems like you know,

00:10:48.080 --> 00:10:51.080
[Amit Varma]: you're in your 30s before you can actually do anything.

00:10:51.080 --> 00:10:54.740
[Amit Varma]: And even then, there is a survivorship bias where you hear of good doctors making a lot

00:10:54.740 --> 00:10:55.740
[Amit Varma]: of money.

00:10:55.740 --> 00:10:59.820
[Amit Varma]: But it's not necessary that at the end of that journey, you will be successful.

00:10:59.820 --> 00:11:04.440
[Amit Varma]: So when you made that final call, I mean, obviously, you must have taken this into account.

00:11:04.440 --> 00:11:06.520
[Amit Varma]: So what was the thinking that went behind it?

00:11:06.520 --> 00:11:10.940
[Amit Varma]: And when you started, did you find that the study of medicine was turning out to be different

00:11:10.940 --> 00:11:11.940
[Amit Varma]: from what you expected?

00:11:11.940 --> 00:11:14.440
[Amit Varma]: Or you knew going in what it was going to be?

00:11:14.440 --> 00:11:18.360
[Amit Varma]: I mean, as you pointed out, there's a Robin Cook influence and all of that.

00:11:18.360 --> 00:11:22.360
[Amit Varma]: So tell me a bit about your decision making during this time, what you expected?

00:11:22.360 --> 00:11:24.420
[Amit Varma]: What did you enjoy about it?

00:11:24.420 --> 00:11:27.880
[Guest]: So it's a very interesting question you asked there, because so one of my closest friends

00:11:27.880 --> 00:11:31.340
[Guest]: in school was a guy who went on to do engineering.

00:11:31.340 --> 00:11:34.840
[Guest]: And I would spend a lot of time at his house, and it was a joint family, they had doctors

00:11:34.840 --> 00:11:36.400
[Guest]: in their house as well.

00:11:36.400 --> 00:11:40.680
[Guest]: And this constant theme that I was reminded of was, you know, you choose medicine, you're

00:11:40.680 --> 00:11:43.680
[Guest]: just going to be studying, you will never make money, you will be studying till you're

00:11:43.680 --> 00:11:44.680
[Guest]: 30-35.

00:11:44.680 --> 00:11:49.280
[Guest]: You know, baal jhar jayenge, which, you know, unfortunately, is true right now.

00:11:49.280 --> 00:11:53.440
[Guest]: But you know, baal jhar jayenge, lekin tumhara, you know, you'll still be studying and, you

00:11:53.440 --> 00:11:58.120
[Guest]: know, obviously, anecdotes of doctors and their kids giving exams together, you know,

00:11:58.120 --> 00:12:02.200
[Guest]: come to the fore, you know, look at him, his second standard son, and he had both giving

00:12:02.200 --> 00:12:03.800
[Guest]: exams at the same time.

00:12:03.800 --> 00:12:08.080
[Guest]: So those kinds of stories were constantly, you were constantly reminded that, you know,

00:12:08.080 --> 00:12:10.320
[Guest]: you may not be making such a good choice.

00:12:10.320 --> 00:12:15.280
[Guest]: You know, one of the things that really is very crystal clear in my head was this conversation

00:12:15.280 --> 00:12:19.960
[Guest]: I had with this guy, whose wife worked for one of the hospitals in Mumbai.

00:12:19.960 --> 00:12:24.520
[Guest]: And I don't remember whether she was a doctor or what was the context.

00:12:24.520 --> 00:12:28.720
[Guest]: But he said something like, listen, you know, you will become a doctor, maybe, you know,

00:12:28.720 --> 00:12:30.540
[Guest]: maybe you'll get into medicine.

00:12:30.540 --> 00:12:34.200
[Guest]: But at the end of medicine, do you know how difficult it is to get a postgraduate seat,

00:12:34.200 --> 00:12:36.680
[Guest]: you know, you will struggle with the postgraduate seat.

00:12:36.680 --> 00:12:41.180
[Guest]: And everybody who doesn't get a postgraduate seat of their choice ends up doing PSM.

00:12:41.180 --> 00:12:43.200
[Guest]: So PSM is preventive and social medicine.

00:12:43.200 --> 00:12:46.160
[Guest]: And this is when I'm in like 10th standard, I don't even know what he's talking about,

00:12:46.160 --> 00:12:47.160
[Guest]: right.

00:12:47.160 --> 00:12:52.480
[Guest]: So he says, you will do PSM, and all you will be telling people to do is wash their hands.

00:12:52.480 --> 00:12:55.800
[Guest]: And the irony is that for the past year, all I've been telling people to do is wash their

00:12:55.800 --> 00:12:57.680
[Guest]: hands, right?

00:12:57.680 --> 00:12:59.920
[Guest]: It's somehow come back a full circle.

00:12:59.920 --> 00:13:05.200
[Guest]: But to answer your question, I guess there is a lot of naivety when you make a choice

00:13:05.200 --> 00:13:09.440
[Guest]: when you're exactly from the background that I am, you know, you are middle class.

00:13:09.440 --> 00:13:13.920
[Guest]: So you don't have a strong safety net in that sense, where you can assume that you will

00:13:13.920 --> 00:13:19.760
[Guest]: study indefinitely, and you know, you will somehow be supported.

00:13:19.760 --> 00:13:21.440
[Guest]: And yet you make this leap of faith.

00:13:21.440 --> 00:13:24.380
[Guest]: And I think that that decision is a difficult decision.

00:13:24.380 --> 00:13:28.840
[Guest]: And I think some of that is is totally naivety, you know, because you don't know, really,

00:13:28.840 --> 00:13:33.500
[Guest]: you've seen only the glamorous part of things, you don't realize that for every doctor who's

00:13:33.500 --> 00:13:37.640
[Guest]: probably you know, in your face looking glamorous looking good, there are probably 10 doctors

00:13:37.640 --> 00:13:41.400
[Guest]: who are really struggling, who are finding it difficult, because it's such a competitive

00:13:41.400 --> 00:13:44.680
[Guest]: field because you know, everyone is pretty intelligent.

00:13:44.680 --> 00:13:50.080
[Guest]: So I think that final leap of faith is very often made against all advice.

00:13:50.080 --> 00:13:52.920
[Guest]: And it's made at a time when you really don't know what's on the other side.

00:13:52.920 --> 00:13:57.400
[Guest]: So it's truly a leap of faith in that sense, you know, so to answer your question, I think,

00:13:57.400 --> 00:14:02.240
[Guest]: you know, as fatalistic as it may sound, I've also believed that things which don't work

00:14:02.240 --> 00:14:04.860
[Guest]: out sometimes just don't work out for a reason.

00:14:04.860 --> 00:14:09.800
[Guest]: So had I not got the requisite marks to make it into medicine, maybe I would have just

00:14:09.800 --> 00:14:13.480
[Guest]: like taken it in my stride and done something else at that point of time.

00:14:13.480 --> 00:14:17.640
[Guest]: But even today, you know, so somebody going through the system, even today, where the

00:14:17.640 --> 00:14:22.400
[Guest]: applicant pool is so high, you have to compete so hard to get into the right kind of colleges

00:14:22.400 --> 00:14:25.120
[Guest]: to get a good education.

00:14:25.120 --> 00:14:26.840
[Guest]: I think there's no simple answer, you know.

00:14:26.840 --> 00:14:32.000
[Guest]: So if somebody asks me today, if somebody in my similar situation, who's in 10th or

00:14:32.000 --> 00:14:36.440
[Guest]: 11th asks me today, whether this is the right choice for me, I will place the facts in front

00:14:36.440 --> 00:14:39.960
[Guest]: of the person, but I will not tell them that it's a no brainer that you know, this is this

00:14:39.960 --> 00:14:43.240
[Guest]: is the best life that you'll ever have, because it is a tough life.

00:14:43.240 --> 00:14:47.520
[Guest]: And you know, I think that that's kind of my answer to your question.

00:14:47.520 --> 00:14:52.120
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, you know, that's very illuminating, because just thinking aloud, you know, I had

00:14:52.120 --> 00:14:57.280
[Amit Varma]: a young person come to me for advice a few months ago, where his mother wanted him to

00:14:57.280 --> 00:14:58.280
[Amit Varma]: do medicine.

00:14:58.280 --> 00:14:59.520
[Amit Varma]: And he was like, what's the scene?

00:14:59.520 --> 00:15:03.360
[Amit Varma]: And I said, Listen, in the end, of course, it is a personal decision, it's up to you.

00:15:03.360 --> 00:15:07.760
[Amit Varma]: But just putting my economics hat on, I would say that the opportunity cost of medicine

00:15:07.760 --> 00:15:08.760
[Amit Varma]: is far higher.

00:15:08.760 --> 00:15:13.240
[Amit Varma]: Because if you decide engineering is not for you, you can do an MBA, you can go to a scroll

00:15:13.240 --> 00:15:17.760
[Amit Varma]: or a wire or the Times of India and say, make me a trainee reporter, or whatever there are

00:15:17.760 --> 00:15:19.320
[Amit Varma]: all those options are kind of there.

00:15:19.320 --> 00:15:23.120
[Amit Varma]: But medicine, you could be 30 by the time you realize you're not going to make it.

00:15:23.120 --> 00:15:24.200
[Amit Varma]: And it could be too late.

00:15:24.200 --> 00:15:28.640
[Amit Varma]: So if all things were equal, satirist parables, it would almost be a no brainer not to do

00:15:28.640 --> 00:15:29.640
[Amit Varma]: medicine.

00:15:29.640 --> 00:15:32.560
[Amit Varma]: But if that's where your heart lies, that's where your heart lies.

00:15:32.560 --> 00:15:37.560
[Amit Varma]: Now, my other question here is that I've spoken to people who say that we got into medicine

00:15:37.560 --> 00:15:41.680
[Amit Varma]: because of a passion for biology, because of the wonder of medicine, like one of my

00:15:41.680 --> 00:15:45.520
[Amit Varma]: friends told me that, you know, one of his parents died of cancer when he was young.

00:15:45.520 --> 00:15:48.160
[Amit Varma]: And he said, I want to find a cure for cancer, right.

00:15:48.160 --> 00:15:49.560
[Amit Varma]: And therefore he gets into medicine.

00:15:49.560 --> 00:15:53.320
[Amit Varma]: But having gotten a certain way along the academic path, he realized that wait a minute,

00:15:53.320 --> 00:15:56.320
[Amit Varma]: doctors don't find a cure for anything, I need to be a scientist.

00:15:56.320 --> 00:15:58.040
[Amit Varma]: And then he goes and he becomes a scientist.

00:15:58.040 --> 00:16:01.000
[Amit Varma]: And now he's a successful academic somewhere.

00:16:01.000 --> 00:16:03.640
[Amit Varma]: So you know, did you go through that kind of process?

00:16:03.640 --> 00:16:08.480
[Amit Varma]: Because a lot of the things that I guess would attract you, which would be intellectually

00:16:08.480 --> 00:16:13.660
[Amit Varma]: attractive or stimulating about the study of medicine would actually be related to science

00:16:13.660 --> 00:16:17.640
[Amit Varma]: and higher research, rather than becoming a practicing doctor to begin with.

00:16:17.640 --> 00:16:21.920
[Amit Varma]: And I'm aware that you have an MSc in epidemiology and all of that, which you went on to do,

00:16:21.920 --> 00:16:23.600
[Amit Varma]: but you are a practicing doctor.

00:16:23.600 --> 00:16:27.240
[Amit Varma]: So obviously, this has to be something that you then thought about.

00:16:27.240 --> 00:16:31.760
[Amit Varma]: And what then made you decide that no, I will practice, I will be a doctor because it seems

00:16:31.760 --> 00:16:36.760
[Amit Varma]: to me that just from the way that I look at it, it feels that in science, you're always

00:16:36.760 --> 00:16:41.160
[Amit Varma]: moving forward, even if it's a little forward incrementally, but you're moving forward.

00:16:41.160 --> 00:16:45.620
[Amit Varma]: While in medicine, it seems that you're running to stand still, you're always trying to kind

00:16:45.620 --> 00:16:48.320
[Amit Varma]: of figure out what is the latest and kind of apply that.

00:16:48.320 --> 00:16:53.040
[Amit Varma]: So how has that process of thinking these things through been for you?

00:16:53.040 --> 00:16:58.120
[Guest]: So I think when people begin, no matter what they begin in terms of their career, I think

00:16:58.120 --> 00:17:02.480
[Guest]: everybody has a very big canvas in mind, they always think that, you know, they're going

00:17:02.480 --> 00:17:04.280
[Guest]: to change the world in some way.

00:17:04.280 --> 00:17:08.400
[Guest]: So if you, you know, if you met someone like, if you met me when I was in my 10th grade

00:17:08.400 --> 00:17:12.160
[Guest]: or my 12th grade and said, you know, what is evidence based medicine?

00:17:12.160 --> 00:17:15.720
[Guest]: Do you know how, how will you make decisions when it comes to patient care?

00:17:15.720 --> 00:17:19.760
[Guest]: I think there was no concept of, of anything like that at that point of time, in the sense

00:17:19.760 --> 00:17:21.720
[Guest]: in on my radar, right?

00:17:21.720 --> 00:17:25.320
[Guest]: So most, most of the decisions are made in terms of what kind of a person do you want

00:17:25.320 --> 00:17:26.320
[Guest]: to be?

00:17:26.320 --> 00:17:30.960
[Guest]: So I was, I was always attracted to this concept of just working hard and giving it your best,

00:17:30.960 --> 00:17:31.960
[Guest]: no matter what.

00:17:31.960 --> 00:17:36.880
[Guest]: And, you know, let things take care of themselves, you know, don't, don't be obsessed about how

00:17:36.880 --> 00:17:38.000
[Guest]: much money you're making.

00:17:38.000 --> 00:17:42.160
[Guest]: Don't be obsessed about what, what is the so-called return on investment, you know,

00:17:42.160 --> 00:17:44.760
[Guest]: which is, which is the whole argument against medicine, right?

00:17:44.760 --> 00:17:47.840
[Guest]: Which everyone reminds you again and again that, you know, when are you going to make

00:17:47.840 --> 00:17:48.840
[Guest]: money?

00:17:48.840 --> 00:17:52.920
[Guest]: And the worst is when you're like around 24 years old, you know, where all your friends,

00:17:52.920 --> 00:17:56.880
[Guest]: the last bencher in your school is also suddenly joined the merchant Navy and he's making like

00:17:56.880 --> 00:17:59.480
[Guest]: 20 times the amount that you are.

00:17:59.480 --> 00:18:02.840
[Guest]: And everybody points out that you've clearly made the wrong decision.

00:18:02.840 --> 00:18:08.080
[Guest]: So I think this, this decision comes from a place of, I think a larger principle that,

00:18:08.080 --> 00:18:11.680
[Guest]: you know, you enjoy at some level helping people.

00:18:11.680 --> 00:18:15.400
[Guest]: I don't necessarily mean in an altruistic way, or I don't mean it, I don't mean it in

00:18:15.400 --> 00:18:16.880
[Guest]: a, in a charitable way.

00:18:16.880 --> 00:18:21.040
[Guest]: I mean it in a way that, you know, somebody comes to you with some sort of a problem,

00:18:21.040 --> 00:18:24.800
[Guest]: you are able to give them some sort of an instant relief, you are able to give them

00:18:24.800 --> 00:18:26.520
[Guest]: solace in some way.

00:18:26.520 --> 00:18:30.000
[Guest]: And that turnaround time is rapid enough that you get the feedback, you feel good about

00:18:30.000 --> 00:18:34.000
[Guest]: it, you feel that you are making a difference on micro levels.

00:18:34.000 --> 00:18:38.400
[Guest]: And I think that's the model, or that's the goal that people are attracted to at that

00:18:38.400 --> 00:18:40.600
[Guest]: stage when, you know, early on.

00:18:40.600 --> 00:18:46.080
[Guest]: Now whether that will cause a big dent in the world, possibly not, you know, but I think

00:18:46.080 --> 00:18:51.080
[Guest]: those little joys on a day to day basis, where even though, you know, as you rightly pointed

00:18:51.080 --> 00:18:54.720
[Guest]: out, you're running to stay in the same place when you look at the macro picture, but at

00:18:54.720 --> 00:18:59.680
[Guest]: the micro picture, you're making small moves every single day, which, which give you a

00:18:59.680 --> 00:19:03.480
[Guest]: lot of instant gratification, which a lot of other fields possibly don't get.

00:19:03.480 --> 00:19:07.400
[Guest]: You know, if you're, and this is my perspective, and I could be completely wrong.

00:19:07.400 --> 00:19:10.520
[Guest]: But say if you're a software engineer, and you're designing software, maybe when the

00:19:10.520 --> 00:19:14.640
[Guest]: product is finally ready one year down the road, you get a lot of gratification and you

00:19:14.640 --> 00:19:16.700
[Guest]: get a lot of sense of achievement.

00:19:16.700 --> 00:19:21.080
[Guest]: But during that one year, it's probably every single day is, is, is tough, you know, because

00:19:21.080 --> 00:19:23.120
[Guest]: you're just writing code maybe.

00:19:23.120 --> 00:19:26.280
[Guest]: But but for a doctor, I think there are a lot of small joys in every single day.

00:19:26.280 --> 00:19:30.280
[Guest]: And I think that's what drives a lot of us, especially in your early years, because you've

00:19:30.280 --> 00:19:35.000
[Guest]: seen you've yourself gone to a doctor at some point of time, you've yourself realized that

00:19:35.000 --> 00:19:38.680
[Guest]: they give you some sort of a salve, some sort of a relief at that point, which makes you

00:19:38.680 --> 00:19:39.680
[Guest]: feel good.

00:19:39.680 --> 00:19:43.760
[Guest]: And I think I think that process is something which is very attractive.

00:19:43.760 --> 00:19:44.760
[Amit Varma]: That's really interesting.

00:19:44.760 --> 00:19:48.000
[Amit Varma]: Because I mean, when you think about it, the world is a positive someplace.

00:19:48.000 --> 00:19:51.520
[Amit Varma]: And we benefit when others benefit, mostly unless you know, you're in the government

00:19:51.520 --> 00:19:53.240
[Amit Varma]: or you're in seeking or whatever.

00:19:53.240 --> 00:19:57.160
[Amit Varma]: But for most of us, the benefit that comes from our work is unseen, it's like really

00:19:57.160 --> 00:20:01.200
[Amit Varma]: the scene in the unseen, that it's way down the road, like you said, if a software engineer

00:20:01.200 --> 00:20:05.280
[Amit Varma]: designed some software, even when the software is out there, he can't really see the benefit,

00:20:05.280 --> 00:20:08.760
[Amit Varma]: he doesn't know how much difference is few lines of code made.

00:20:08.760 --> 00:20:11.920
[Amit Varma]: Maybe if he works in Microsoft, maybe that's what made Windows hang.

00:20:11.920 --> 00:20:16.720
[Amit Varma]: But in your case, it's a little more immediate, which is fascinating to me.

00:20:16.720 --> 00:20:20.800
[Amit Varma]: It also sort of strikes me that, you know, when we think of experts, when we think of

00:20:20.800 --> 00:20:25.120
[Amit Varma]: the professionals, we think of them as people who know their field.

00:20:25.120 --> 00:20:28.960
[Amit Varma]: But I think what often happens is in many fields, whether it is medicine or economics

00:20:28.960 --> 00:20:34.360
[Amit Varma]: or whatever, in all fields, there's a set of people who are not really actively engaged

00:20:34.360 --> 00:20:38.560
[Amit Varma]: in that sense, they are doing the degree, they get the knowledge, and that is a knowledge

00:20:38.560 --> 00:20:39.560
[Amit Varma]: they have.

00:20:39.560 --> 00:20:42.640
[Amit Varma]: And very often, it's kind of a static kind of knowledge.

00:20:42.640 --> 00:20:46.520
[Amit Varma]: And they don't have the intellectual curiosity to maybe apply their frame to other things

00:20:46.520 --> 00:20:50.280
[Amit Varma]: and constantly broaden, constantly read all of that.

00:20:50.280 --> 00:20:53.920
[Amit Varma]: And you know, I noticed this most with some economists, you know, there are really two

00:20:53.920 --> 00:20:57.200
[Amit Varma]: kinds of economists, those who are thinking actively about the world.

00:20:57.200 --> 00:21:00.720
[Amit Varma]: And those who have done the training, who can make the charts and do the regressions

00:21:00.720 --> 00:21:05.160
[Amit Varma]: and all that, but aren't really thinking that actively now with doctors also, it seems to

00:21:05.160 --> 00:21:09.720
[Amit Varma]: me that we think of doctors as experts, we have a problem, we go to a doc, doc will solve

00:21:09.720 --> 00:21:10.720
[Amit Varma]: it.

00:21:10.720 --> 00:21:16.040
[Amit Varma]: But very often, you know, a doctor say trained in the 1990s, was trained in what was in many

00:21:16.040 --> 00:21:21.200
[Amit Varma]: fields, very outdated knowledge, for example, nutrition, right, where for the longest time

00:21:21.200 --> 00:21:25.480
[Amit Varma]: for decades, you know, the sugar lobby funded all these studies at Harvard and all that

00:21:25.480 --> 00:21:27.840
[Amit Varma]: in the 1950s and 60s.

00:21:27.840 --> 00:21:32.360
[Amit Varma]: And you know, fat was demonized, sugar was supposed to be okay.

00:21:32.360 --> 00:21:36.040
[Amit Varma]: And the American government released guidelines to this effect in the late 1970s.

00:21:36.040 --> 00:21:38.320
[Amit Varma]: And their obesity epidemic begins from there.

00:21:38.320 --> 00:21:42.320
[Amit Varma]: And in something like the last 10 to 15 years, it's kind of become common knowledge that

00:21:42.320 --> 00:21:46.880
[Amit Varma]: all of this is kind of rubbish, we've been obsessing over the wrong things, sugar is

00:21:46.880 --> 00:21:47.880
[Amit Varma]: the real problem.

00:21:47.880 --> 00:21:50.900
[Amit Varma]: Now, one of my friends went to a doctor recently to ask about nutrition.

00:21:50.900 --> 00:21:54.960
[Amit Varma]: And he got that old dogma, because she hadn't read up and updated herself on the state of

00:21:54.960 --> 00:21:56.040
[Amit Varma]: the science.

00:21:56.040 --> 00:22:01.040
[Amit Varma]: So a two part question really that when you were studying, did you notice this difference

00:22:01.040 --> 00:22:05.600
[Amit Varma]: in approach that there are people who just want to understand what is in the books and

00:22:05.600 --> 00:22:07.280
[Amit Varma]: do well in the exams.

00:22:07.280 --> 00:22:11.480
[Amit Varma]: And there are people who are naturally curious, who are reading more, and therefore who are

00:22:11.480 --> 00:22:17.640
[Amit Varma]: more likely in future to stay updated with whatever the state of the science is.

00:22:17.640 --> 00:22:21.760
[Guest]: I think part of that is the problem in which medical education occurs.

00:22:21.760 --> 00:22:24.200
[Guest]: And you know, it's very fact heavy.

00:22:24.200 --> 00:22:26.000
[Guest]: So let's look at medical textbooks, right?

00:22:26.000 --> 00:22:29.920
[Guest]: So I mean, most of us have this God textbook for every subject under the sun.

00:22:29.920 --> 00:22:32.480
[Guest]: So if you're studying anatomy, this is the God textbook.

00:22:32.480 --> 00:22:34.840
[Guest]: If you're studying physiology, this is the God textbook.

00:22:34.840 --> 00:22:38.760
[Guest]: Now, I've been part of a process of knowing how textbooks are written.

00:22:38.760 --> 00:22:43.600
[Guest]: And if you look at how textbooks are written, the time gap between when the decision to

00:22:43.600 --> 00:22:47.120
[Guest]: write the textbook begins to the textbook actually being published is usually around

00:22:47.120 --> 00:22:48.800
[Guest]: two to three years.

00:22:48.800 --> 00:22:53.160
[Guest]: So when it actually gets published, some of the stuff was current and relevant three years

00:22:53.160 --> 00:22:58.080
[Guest]: ago and is probably already been surpassed by newer knowledge or superseded by a newer

00:22:58.080 --> 00:23:00.140
[Guest]: study which has happened.

00:23:00.140 --> 00:23:04.440
[Guest]: So if you bank completely on textbooks, you're not going to get state of the art knowledge.

00:23:04.440 --> 00:23:07.120
[Guest]: However, medical education gives a lot of focus on textbooks.

00:23:07.120 --> 00:23:11.240
[Guest]: So that's one example where you are taught to keep sticking to the facts which are written

00:23:11.240 --> 00:23:14.320
[Guest]: in the textbook that's written in stone because it's this God textbook.

00:23:14.320 --> 00:23:17.820
[Guest]: It's this Bible of a particular subject.

00:23:17.820 --> 00:23:20.880
[Guest]: You are not taught the methodology to critique things.

00:23:20.880 --> 00:23:23.200
[Guest]: You are taught to remember the facts.

00:23:23.200 --> 00:23:26.540
[Guest]: You are not really trained in how to critique facts.

00:23:26.540 --> 00:23:31.160
[Guest]: So if that training comes into play, then you would have this healthy discussion which

00:23:31.160 --> 00:23:33.720
[Guest]: would constantly happen, which happens in academia, right?

00:23:33.720 --> 00:23:37.360
[Guest]: Where somebody says something and another person points out and says, but listen, there

00:23:37.360 --> 00:23:40.300
[Guest]: was this newer study which was published just two days ago.

00:23:40.300 --> 00:23:41.560
[Guest]: Have you gone through it?

00:23:41.560 --> 00:23:47.520
[Guest]: And that constant debate, that constant being the constant chatter among academics, which

00:23:47.520 --> 00:23:52.360
[Guest]: makes one realize that, you know, you need to constantly update yourself is very often

00:23:52.360 --> 00:23:54.000
[Guest]: lacking in medical schools.

00:23:54.000 --> 00:23:55.000
[Guest]: That is a big problem.

00:23:55.000 --> 00:23:58.720
[Guest]: So that you are not taught really to question.

00:23:58.720 --> 00:24:03.760
[Guest]: Now whether that divides the world into two parts, I don't think it's that straightforward.

00:24:03.760 --> 00:24:09.840
[Guest]: I think most of us with a medical education come out again with the same concepts of truths

00:24:09.840 --> 00:24:12.600
[Guest]: being absolutely written in stone.

00:24:12.600 --> 00:24:18.200
[Guest]: It's when you start practicing, if you are curious enough, if you realize that, you know,

00:24:18.200 --> 00:24:22.880
[Guest]: every patient does not fit into a particular mold, if you start questioning why something's

00:24:22.880 --> 00:24:27.080
[Guest]: happening in a certain way when you expected it to happen the other way, if you then get

00:24:27.080 --> 00:24:31.960
[Guest]: into a process of constantly searching, constantly reviewing the literature, I think that that

00:24:31.960 --> 00:24:33.740
[Guest]: makes a lot of difference.

00:24:33.740 --> 00:24:36.160
[Guest]: Now part of that is also a function of time.

00:24:36.160 --> 00:24:41.640
[Guest]: So it is extremely difficult for doctors to continuously update themselves, which is why

00:24:41.640 --> 00:24:44.000
[Guest]: it would be nice if there were simpler guidelines, right?

00:24:44.000 --> 00:24:45.520
[Guest]: I mean, that's what we all want.

00:24:45.520 --> 00:24:49.960
[Guest]: We want some sort of a guideline that's constantly updated, or some sort of a course which we

00:24:49.960 --> 00:24:54.120
[Guest]: can attend once a year where we get updated and change our practice.

00:24:54.120 --> 00:24:59.080
[Guest]: Now expecting a practicing doctor to be able to continuously update themselves is a tough

00:24:59.080 --> 00:25:00.320
[Guest]: task.

00:25:00.320 --> 00:25:05.520
[Guest]: And the way it works, unfortunately or unfortunately, in medicine is that the older you get, the

00:25:05.520 --> 00:25:11.600
[Guest]: more senior you get, your patient base increases and, you know, there's word of mouth, there's

00:25:11.600 --> 00:25:16.200
[Guest]: a general awareness of a particular doctor of a particular specialty being there.

00:25:16.200 --> 00:25:19.520
[Guest]: And that just means that you're getting busier and busier and therefore having lesser and

00:25:19.520 --> 00:25:21.480
[Guest]: lesser time to update yourself.

00:25:21.480 --> 00:25:25.360
[Guest]: And unfortunately, this then becomes a common trajectory for a lot of doctors and, you know,

00:25:25.360 --> 00:25:30.120
[Guest]: even I hope this doesn't happen to me, but that's the natural drift, unfortunately, that

00:25:30.120 --> 00:25:34.520
[Guest]: you get busy, you get popular, you get more patients, less time to read, and gradually

00:25:34.520 --> 00:25:36.680
[Guest]: you start doing things which are outdated.

00:25:36.680 --> 00:25:39.760
[Guest]: And I think this needs to be rethought, you know, we need to figure out a way to get out

00:25:39.760 --> 00:25:42.120
[Amit Varma]: of this.

00:25:42.120 --> 00:25:44.520
[Amit Varma]: And how does one keep in touch with latest research then?

00:25:44.520 --> 00:25:46.640
[Amit Varma]: Like, is the internet a game changer there?

00:25:46.640 --> 00:25:51.440
[Amit Varma]: Because I would assume that pre the internet for a practicing doctor to want to keep in

00:25:51.440 --> 00:25:55.480
[Amit Varma]: touch with the latest in the field, especially if you're in India, and all the latest research

00:25:55.480 --> 00:26:00.320
[Amit Varma]: and all that is happening in the US is incredibly difficult, but now it should be kind of easier.

00:26:00.320 --> 00:26:04.360
[Amit Varma]: So what are your practices like, are there journals you go to, do you spend a certain

00:26:04.360 --> 00:26:05.920
[Amit Varma]: amount of time reading papers?

00:26:05.920 --> 00:26:11.880
[Amit Varma]: Do you tell yourself that X percent of the time I must devote to updating myself or,

00:26:11.880 --> 00:26:12.960
[Amit Varma]: you know, leveling up?

00:26:12.960 --> 00:26:15.040
[Guest]: How does that process kind of work for you?

00:26:15.040 --> 00:26:19.080
[Guest]: So I think one of the best ways of keeping yourself updated on the literature is having

00:26:19.080 --> 00:26:20.080
[Guest]: students, right?

00:26:20.080 --> 00:26:23.560
[Guest]: And I have the luxury of having students, I'm at a teaching institute.

00:26:23.560 --> 00:26:28.040
[Guest]: So when you teach students, you automatically update yourself on the latest literature.

00:26:28.040 --> 00:26:33.160
[Guest]: If you inculcate that hunger in them, students have this natural questioning hunger, which

00:26:33.160 --> 00:26:36.840
[Guest]: they will, you know, they will pose questions to you on rounds sometimes saying that, you

00:26:36.840 --> 00:26:38.920
[Guest]: know, is this the right way of doing things?

00:26:38.920 --> 00:26:41.160
[Guest]: And that again, needs to be fostered.

00:26:41.160 --> 00:26:44.720
[Guest]: If you go by the didactic method, that it's my way or the highway, you know, this is right

00:26:44.720 --> 00:26:50.560
[Guest]: because boss says so, you will end up having your knowledge not updated because, you know,

00:26:50.560 --> 00:26:52.880
[Guest]: where you are at is where you will be.

00:26:52.880 --> 00:26:57.560
[Guest]: Your students will not question you and you will keep perpetuating the same cycle.

00:26:57.560 --> 00:27:01.840
[Guest]: If you have students who constantly ask you or, and you can ask them as well, you know,

00:27:01.840 --> 00:27:05.480
[Guest]: why don't you read up on this and tell me more about this, that exchange keeps you updated

00:27:05.480 --> 00:27:07.000
[Guest]: and it's very useful.

00:27:07.000 --> 00:27:09.960
[Guest]: But then again, I have the luxury of being in a teaching institute.

00:27:09.960 --> 00:27:14.280
[Guest]: If you're not at a teaching institute, fortunately, there are a lot of, I don't know what they're

00:27:14.280 --> 00:27:15.280
[Guest]: called.

00:27:15.280 --> 00:27:19.680
[Guest]: They probably like meta websites, which have started compiling literature from all the

00:27:19.680 --> 00:27:20.680
[Guest]: available evidence.

00:27:20.680 --> 00:27:24.120
[Guest]: And, you know, the thing that comes to mind, which I use on a day-to-day basis is something

00:27:24.120 --> 00:27:25.760
[Guest]: called up-to-date.

00:27:25.760 --> 00:27:30.720
[Guest]: So up-to-date is a website, which also has an app on your phone now, where they get experts

00:27:30.720 --> 00:27:35.560
[Guest]: in a particular field to write a particular topic and that expert will cover the topic

00:27:35.560 --> 00:27:37.080
[Guest]: through and through.

00:27:37.080 --> 00:27:40.440
[Guest]: The experts are also incentivized to update it every year or so.

00:27:40.440 --> 00:27:44.320
[Guest]: I think, you know, they're actually paid, I know, because some of my supervisors have

00:27:44.320 --> 00:27:48.240
[Guest]: written topics here and they're incentivized to keep updating the topic.

00:27:48.240 --> 00:27:52.560
[Guest]: So supposing I have this patient sitting in front of me who I think has this rare lung

00:27:52.560 --> 00:27:56.240
[Guest]: disorder and I've, you know, the last time I've seen a patient with something like this

00:27:56.240 --> 00:27:57.400
[Guest]: was about three years back.

00:27:57.400 --> 00:28:01.220
[Guest]: So clearly I'm not going to be by default updated on the literature because it's not

00:28:01.220 --> 00:28:02.480
[Guest]: being on my radar.

00:28:02.480 --> 00:28:04.820
[Guest]: I haven't actively searched for this disease.

00:28:04.820 --> 00:28:08.720
[Guest]: So I go to up-to-date, I open it and very often, you know, I will come to know if there's

00:28:08.720 --> 00:28:13.080
[Guest]: a new drug available, if there's a new therapy that has been tried somewhere, there are links

00:28:13.080 --> 00:28:18.040
[Guest]: sometimes which will take me to earlier studies, and then I can choose to go into a deep dive.

00:28:18.040 --> 00:28:21.920
[Guest]: So up-to-date will summarize what the literature is, give me the references for those papers.

00:28:21.920 --> 00:28:27.080
[Guest]: I can then go and dig out those papers myself, critique those papers, see if they make sense

00:28:27.080 --> 00:28:28.480
[Guest]: and summarize.

00:28:28.480 --> 00:28:33.960
[Guest]: But this is not as easy as it sounds in the sense that you're trying to do all of this

00:28:33.960 --> 00:28:36.840
[Guest]: in the middle of an OPD, in the middle of a clinic.

00:28:36.840 --> 00:28:39.800
[Guest]: So I have sometimes told patients, let me read up.

00:28:39.800 --> 00:28:44.720
[Guest]: I open this in front of the patient and I do it, but I can see how a lot of people would

00:28:44.720 --> 00:28:48.660
[Guest]: feel that doing that would make the patient question their credentials.

00:28:48.660 --> 00:28:52.840
[Guest]: So I think we need to also create a healthy atmosphere where, you know, the doctor doesn't

00:28:52.840 --> 00:28:53.840
[Guest]: know all the answers.

00:28:53.840 --> 00:28:58.200
[Guest]: The doctor will update his knowledge if necessary in front of you.

00:28:58.200 --> 00:29:01.000
[Guest]: The doctor is someone who will give you the best knowledge as of today.

00:29:01.000 --> 00:29:06.360
[Guest]: How he gets there could be a journey, could involve some time on your part.

00:29:06.360 --> 00:29:09.600
[Guest]: He doesn't need to be an encyclopedia with all the answers ready.

00:29:09.600 --> 00:29:14.560
[Guest]: As long as we start moving to that modality where even patients accept that, you know,

00:29:14.560 --> 00:29:18.480
[Guest]: accept a doctor who's searching in front of them, accept a doctor who says, I don't know.

00:29:18.480 --> 00:29:19.560
[Guest]: I think that's great.

00:29:19.560 --> 00:29:23.400
[Guest]: So when I talk to my friends and relatives, I tell them very often that the doctor you

00:29:23.400 --> 00:29:29.280
[Guest]: want is the doctor who once in a while says, I don't know the answer to this question.

00:29:29.280 --> 00:29:33.760
[Guest]: If you have a doctor who knows the answer to every question, then that's, you know,

00:29:33.760 --> 00:29:39.000
[Guest]: I mean, it could be exceptionally good, of course, but, you know, that would be a rarity.

00:29:39.000 --> 00:29:43.120
[Amit Varma]: You know, this leads me into a digression on what patients really expect from their

00:29:43.120 --> 00:29:44.120
[Amit Varma]: doctors.

00:29:44.120 --> 00:29:46.760
[Amit Varma]: And I think in India, at least, they expect a veneer of knowledge.

00:29:46.760 --> 00:29:50.760
[Amit Varma]: They expect their doctor to be like an expert, to have the definitive answers, to give them

00:29:50.760 --> 00:29:51.760
[Amit Varma]: medicines.

00:29:51.760 --> 00:29:56.080
[Amit Varma]: Look, you know, as you have also pointed out in the past, this is what leads to overprescription

00:29:56.080 --> 00:29:57.080
[Amit Varma]: and all of that.

00:29:57.080 --> 00:29:59.920
[Amit Varma]: I remember I read an episode on healthcare with the economist Karthik Murali Tharan and

00:29:59.920 --> 00:30:06.160
[Amit Varma]: he referred to this study in 2007, where, you know, the author of the study asked a

00:30:06.160 --> 00:30:10.080
[Amit Varma]: doctor in a slum so that, you know, when someone has diarrhea, what do you give them?

00:30:10.080 --> 00:30:12.040
[Amit Varma]: And the person listed out a bunch of medicines.

00:30:12.040 --> 00:30:15.840
[Amit Varma]: And then the guy asked that, you know, why don't you just give them oral rehydration?

00:30:15.840 --> 00:30:16.840
[Amit Varma]: Because that's enough.

00:30:16.840 --> 00:30:17.840
[Amit Varma]: That's what WHO recommends.

00:30:17.840 --> 00:30:21.320
[Amit Varma]: And he said, no, because then they won't come to me, they've come to a doctor, they expect

00:30:21.320 --> 00:30:22.840
[Amit Varma]: a bunch of medicines.

00:30:22.840 --> 00:30:23.840
[Amit Varma]: That's what I do.

00:30:23.840 --> 00:30:26.400
[Amit Varma]: If I don't do that, they'll go to someone else, I lose income.

00:30:26.400 --> 00:30:29.920
[Amit Varma]: And that's something, by the way, in India that it's not just doctors, it's we expect

00:30:29.920 --> 00:30:34.280
[Amit Varma]: all our experts to be full of certainty, while the truth is that those who know the most

00:30:34.280 --> 00:30:37.320
[Amit Varma]: will have the least certainty because they'll know how much they don't know.

00:30:37.320 --> 00:30:42.400
[Amit Varma]: Whereas, you know, it's a Dunning-Kruger effect that it's often the fools who have the greatest

00:30:42.400 --> 00:30:46.040
[Amit Varma]: certainty, not to say that doctors are necessarily like that.

00:30:46.040 --> 00:30:47.440
[Amit Varma]: So what do you feel about this?

00:30:47.440 --> 00:30:52.840
[Amit Varma]: Do you feel that there is also this kind of interaction where you not only have to find

00:30:52.840 --> 00:30:57.440
[Amit Varma]: the best treatment, but you also have to live up to the patient's expectations?

00:30:57.440 --> 00:31:01.360
[Amit Varma]: So is it like a game theoretic problem somewhere where there are trade-offs you have to consider?

00:31:01.360 --> 00:31:02.360
[Guest]: Absolutely.

00:31:02.360 --> 00:31:03.680
[Guest]: I couldn't agree more.

00:31:03.680 --> 00:31:07.680
[Guest]: So you gave a context in which you have a diagnosis.

00:31:07.680 --> 00:31:11.920
[Guest]: I often have to face a situation where I tell the patient, listen, we need to do a few tests,

00:31:11.920 --> 00:31:16.680
[Guest]: you know, we'll do these tests, we'll meet up again with the results of these tests.

00:31:16.680 --> 00:31:18.480
[Guest]: And then we'll talk about what needs to be done.

00:31:18.480 --> 00:31:23.280
[Guest]: And on their way out, they very often will turn back and say, but what have you given

00:31:23.280 --> 00:31:25.480
[Guest]: me in treatment today?

00:31:25.480 --> 00:31:28.920
[Guest]: And I need to tell them that I don't know what you have, you know, I genuinely don't

00:31:28.920 --> 00:31:29.920
[Guest]: know what you have.

00:31:29.920 --> 00:31:32.240
[Guest]: How can I treat you if I don't know what you have?

00:31:32.240 --> 00:31:35.960
[Guest]: And they still will very often insist that, you know, but just give me something for today.

00:31:35.960 --> 00:31:42.080
[Guest]: You know, it's almost like this whole interaction is incomplete till there is a prescription

00:31:42.080 --> 00:31:43.160
[Guest]: prescribing drugs.

00:31:43.160 --> 00:31:46.080
[Guest]: You know, it's not just a prescription with tests.

00:31:46.080 --> 00:31:49.520
[Guest]: It has to be a prescription prescribing drugs because I've come to you with a problem and

00:31:49.520 --> 00:31:52.540
[Guest]: you have to give me a fix in some way.

00:31:52.540 --> 00:31:58.720
[Guest]: So I completely empathize, you know, so there is no judgment on my part when I see doctors,

00:31:58.720 --> 00:32:03.800
[Guest]: you know, starting off people on a bunch of medications or doctors being forced to order

00:32:03.800 --> 00:32:09.120
[Guest]: tests sometimes, because we've created this sort of a culture where, you know, a doctor

00:32:09.120 --> 00:32:14.080
[Guest]: who prescribes a lot and I get better is the right doctor.

00:32:14.080 --> 00:32:18.400
[Guest]: The doctor who says take nothing, even if I get better, but he didn't give me anything.

00:32:18.400 --> 00:32:23.160
[Guest]: So it's not, it's basul nahi hua, as you say in Hindi, you know, there was, it didn't complete

00:32:23.160 --> 00:32:24.160
[Guest]: the interaction.

00:32:24.160 --> 00:32:25.160
[Guest]: What did I pay him so much for?

00:32:25.160 --> 00:32:27.240
[Guest]: You know, why did I waste my time going there?

00:32:27.240 --> 00:32:29.240
[Guest]: I didn't get anything out of it.

00:32:29.240 --> 00:32:31.960
[Guest]: So I think this is a genuine problem.

00:32:31.960 --> 00:32:36.880
[Guest]: And I think we need to start thinking in terms of how to let people know that medicines are

00:32:36.880 --> 00:32:39.320
[Guest]: not a solution for every problem.

00:32:39.320 --> 00:32:43.120
[Guest]: And going on and on indefinitely with medicines are also not a solution, you know.

00:32:43.120 --> 00:32:45.080
[Guest]: And there are some problems which can be fixed.

00:32:45.080 --> 00:32:48.960
[Guest]: There are some problems to which, you know, there are no solutions sometimes you just

00:32:48.960 --> 00:32:50.800
[Guest]: have to have to accept that.

00:32:50.800 --> 00:32:54.680
[Guest]: I mean, we talk about all these fancy things and, you know, cutting edge stuff and doing

00:32:54.680 --> 00:32:59.520
[Guest]: scans while as you look at respiratory medicine, something as simple as cough.

00:32:59.520 --> 00:33:04.480
[Guest]: You know, there are people who are doing PhDs in cough as of today, you know, after centuries

00:33:04.480 --> 00:33:09.680
[Guest]: and centuries of coughing, we still don't know what really causes cough in certain circumstances.

00:33:09.680 --> 00:33:12.320
[Guest]: We still don't know where the receptors exactly might be.

00:33:12.320 --> 00:33:15.000
[Guest]: We still don't know what is the drug that will actually work.

00:33:15.000 --> 00:33:19.840
[Guest]: I remember meeting this world expert in cough and he runs a cough clinic.

00:33:19.840 --> 00:33:23.560
[Guest]: And I said, you know, how do you, there was a particular example I gave him and I said,

00:33:23.560 --> 00:33:24.560
[Guest]: how do you treat it?

00:33:24.560 --> 00:33:27.040
[Guest]: So he says, listen, my clinic's very busy.

00:33:27.040 --> 00:33:29.880
[Guest]: So I cannot, you know, see people frequently.

00:33:29.880 --> 00:33:31.840
[Guest]: So I can see them maybe once a month.

00:33:31.840 --> 00:33:35.160
[Guest]: So I take any four random drugs which work on cough generally.

00:33:35.160 --> 00:33:38.640
[Guest]: I say if week one you try this, if this doesn't work, week two you try this, if that doesn't

00:33:38.640 --> 00:33:41.920
[Guest]: work, week three you try this, if that doesn't work, week four you try this.

00:33:41.920 --> 00:33:45.120
[Guest]: And he says, for all you know, nature cures them at some point of time and then the patient

00:33:45.120 --> 00:33:48.960
[Guest]: attributes the cure to that last medication, you know.

00:33:48.960 --> 00:33:49.960
[Guest]: So that's how it is.

00:33:49.960 --> 00:33:55.120
[Guest]: You know, people want some sort of a medicine as a solution for every problem.

00:33:55.120 --> 00:33:57.840
[Guest]: And I think we need to do something to counter that.

00:33:57.840 --> 00:34:02.640
[Amit Varma]: No, in fact, you know, what you said reminded me of the common phenomenon of regression

00:34:02.640 --> 00:34:03.640
[Amit Varma]: to the mean, right?

00:34:03.640 --> 00:34:06.080
[Amit Varma]: Like, why do, for example, people think homeopathy works?

00:34:06.080 --> 00:34:09.640
[Amit Varma]: Part of it is, of course, a placebo effect, but part of it is if you take homeopathy for

00:34:09.640 --> 00:34:13.000
[Amit Varma]: something that's going to get better anyway, you will ascribe causation.

00:34:13.000 --> 00:34:14.640
[Amit Varma]: You will say, oh, this cured me.

00:34:14.640 --> 00:34:17.920
[Amit Varma]: And this could also be true of any cocktail of medicines that the doctor gives you for

00:34:17.920 --> 00:34:22.000
[Amit Varma]: a particular point where you got better on your own, but hey, you feel this worked and

00:34:22.000 --> 00:34:25.000
[Amit Varma]: you know, you will give credit to the medicine and therefore to the doctor.

00:34:25.000 --> 00:34:29.120
[Amit Varma]: And this, of course, happens in politics also where, you know, Amit Shah recently came out

00:34:29.120 --> 00:34:32.360
[Amit Varma]: and said that, you know, Narendra Modi ji has solved the second wave.

00:34:32.360 --> 00:34:34.160
[Amit Varma]: And I'm like, that's regression to the mean, right?

00:34:34.160 --> 00:34:38.020
[Amit Varma]: The second wave at some point in time would have gone down in the most extreme case with

00:34:38.020 --> 00:34:41.400
[Amit Varma]: everyone dying, but whatever happens, a wave would have gone down.

00:34:41.400 --> 00:34:46.120
[Amit Varma]: So the fact of it going down alone is not reason enough to take credit.

00:34:46.120 --> 00:34:48.980
[Amit Varma]: But I don't want to draw you into that kind of political stuff.

00:34:48.980 --> 00:34:49.980
[Amit Varma]: What am I even doing?

00:34:49.980 --> 00:34:55.220
[Amit Varma]: A couple of interesting things, like one thing that sort of strikes me is that when it comes

00:34:55.220 --> 00:35:00.640
[Amit Varma]: to the practice of medicine itself, especially I'm assuming in a place like India, I think

00:35:00.640 --> 00:35:05.060
[Amit Varma]: two things would happen for a doctor and I'm just sort of thinking aloud and you can enlighten

00:35:05.060 --> 00:35:08.500
[Amit Varma]: me on whether these processes actually happen and all of that.

00:35:08.500 --> 00:35:12.360
[Amit Varma]: One is because you're seeing a multiple number of patients and you do not have unlimited

00:35:12.360 --> 00:35:17.120
[Amit Varma]: time for each one, you develop these what economists call fast and frugal heuristics

00:35:17.120 --> 00:35:21.800
[Amit Varma]: by which you figure out that, okay, this is the symptom and this is likely to be the most

00:35:21.800 --> 00:35:22.960
[Amit Varma]: common cause for it.

00:35:22.960 --> 00:35:25.280
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, let me try this and all of that.

00:35:25.280 --> 00:35:27.400
[Amit Varma]: And how does that process work?

00:35:27.400 --> 00:35:31.080
[Amit Varma]: Because initially as a young person, you must be enthusiastic, you want to get to the root

00:35:31.080 --> 00:35:32.160
[Amit Varma]: of everything.

00:35:32.160 --> 00:35:37.000
[Amit Varma]: Is there a point in time when you realize that in practical terms, it is not possible

00:35:37.000 --> 00:35:40.760
[Amit Varma]: and I'll let you answer this first and then I'll go on to my next one.

00:35:40.760 --> 00:35:45.880
[Guest]: So that's again the unfortunate part of medicine, you know, the better you get, the more successful

00:35:45.880 --> 00:35:49.760
[Guest]: you get, the larger the volume of patients you have, the larger the volume of patients

00:35:49.760 --> 00:35:52.760
[Guest]: you have, the lesser time you spend with each one of them.

00:35:52.760 --> 00:35:56.200
[Guest]: And then, you know, exactly what you said, you're pretty much triaging in your head.

00:35:56.200 --> 00:36:02.720
[Guest]: Is this person in dire need for some emergent treatment or is this person not so bad where,

00:36:02.720 --> 00:36:05.800
[Guest]: you know, we can just quickly give him something, send him off, you know, maybe nature takes

00:36:05.800 --> 00:36:06.800
[Guest]: care of it.

00:36:06.800 --> 00:36:08.560
[Guest]: Maybe he gets better and he comes back.

00:36:08.560 --> 00:36:11.680
[Guest]: If it doesn't, then he comes back to me and maybe that second time round is where I really

00:36:11.680 --> 00:36:15.760
[Guest]: spend more time because now I realize that, you know, that quick three minute consult

00:36:15.760 --> 00:36:17.040
[Guest]: wasn't good enough.

00:36:17.040 --> 00:36:21.400
[Guest]: I completely agree with you, you know, the unfortunate part of becoming successful and

00:36:21.400 --> 00:36:26.760
[Guest]: being good at something, in medicine especially, is that eventually it leads to large volumes.

00:36:26.760 --> 00:36:30.920
[Guest]: And I think one of the ways in which you can solve this problem is by having a team.

00:36:30.920 --> 00:36:35.280
[Guest]: So if you have a good second rung, if you have a good bunch of assistants working with

00:36:35.280 --> 00:36:39.560
[Guest]: you, kind of filter things out, you know, give you a brief, quick summary of what's

00:36:39.560 --> 00:36:44.400
[Guest]: happening and then you act on that summary, I think that makes a big difference.

00:36:44.400 --> 00:36:48.080
[Guest]: Because otherwise, you know, exactly what you said, it becomes like quick algorithms.

00:36:48.080 --> 00:36:52.760
[Guest]: Everything becomes algorithmic and whoever doesn't fit into that algorithm is a problem.

00:36:52.760 --> 00:36:53.760
[Guest]: So let me give you an example.

00:36:53.760 --> 00:36:58.360
[Guest]: You know, since we're talking about COVID-19, so one of the things that has been a common

00:36:58.360 --> 00:37:02.720
[Guest]: problem over the past year is individuals who've come to me with breathlessness who

00:37:02.720 --> 00:37:07.320
[Guest]: are actually sighing, you know, because of anxiety, you take a deep breath and you breathe

00:37:07.320 --> 00:37:11.440
[Guest]: out and that, you know, there are natural processes which lower your heart rate when

00:37:11.440 --> 00:37:12.440
[Guest]: you do that.

00:37:12.440 --> 00:37:15.580
[Guest]: There are natural processes which calm you when you do that.

00:37:15.580 --> 00:37:19.320
[Guest]: So it's almost like an epidemic of sighing that I've seen over the past year.

00:37:19.320 --> 00:37:23.800
[Guest]: And these individuals, if you go down that same algorithmic route, somebody says they

00:37:23.800 --> 00:37:27.640
[Guest]: are breathless, you know, do a whole bunch of tests, you know, and then find nothing

00:37:27.640 --> 00:37:28.640
[Guest]: wrong.

00:37:28.640 --> 00:37:32.420
[Guest]: Then you try some inhaler, you try something, I mean, you can completely go down that route.

00:37:32.420 --> 00:37:36.680
[Guest]: But very often, if you just spend like 30 seconds looking at that person and talking

00:37:36.680 --> 00:37:41.400
[Guest]: to that person, you will realize that during that conversation itself, the person sighs

00:37:41.400 --> 00:37:46.480
[Guest]: a couple of times, and you realize that the person is in a hospital, the person is anxious,

00:37:46.480 --> 00:37:47.920
[Guest]: and clearly that person is sighing.

00:37:47.920 --> 00:37:52.280
[Guest]: You ask them when they sleep at night, do they sigh or get up breathless?

00:37:52.280 --> 00:37:54.880
[Guest]: And the answer to that is almost always no.

00:37:54.880 --> 00:37:58.560
[Guest]: So clearly, you know, whatever the problem is, is not happening at night, which again

00:37:58.560 --> 00:38:04.320
[Guest]: points towards a psychological problem, something that's making the person anxious.

00:38:04.320 --> 00:38:07.240
[Guest]: And again, you know, this is why it's important to spend time.

00:38:07.240 --> 00:38:11.080
[Guest]: This is why it's important to observe patients and realize what's happening.

00:38:11.080 --> 00:38:12.080
[Amit Varma]: This is mind blowing.

00:38:12.080 --> 00:38:13.080
[Amit Varma]: An epidemic of sighing.

00:38:13.080 --> 00:38:14.080
[Amit Varma]: Wow.

00:38:14.080 --> 00:38:15.080
[Amit Varma]: Another question.

00:38:15.080 --> 00:38:19.440
[Amit Varma]: My last episode was with Kavita Krishnan, and in that we briefly spoke about Mary Wollstonecraft,

00:38:19.440 --> 00:38:24.720
[Amit Varma]: the great feminist author of the early 19th century or the late 18th century, really.

00:38:24.720 --> 00:38:28.280
[Amit Varma]: And one of the tragedies there is that she died young because she died during childbirth.

00:38:28.280 --> 00:38:33.320
[Amit Varma]: In fact, she gave birth to Mary Shelley, who would later marry the poet, and she died three

00:38:33.320 --> 00:38:36.640
[Amit Varma]: days after childbirth, I think because the doctor didn't wash his hands, right?

00:38:36.640 --> 00:38:39.280
[Amit Varma]: Because that basic protocol was not known at the time.

00:38:39.280 --> 00:38:42.000
[Amit Varma]: That is something that happened in the middle of the 19th century.

00:38:42.000 --> 00:38:47.200
[Amit Varma]: Ignaz Semmelweis said that, you know, correlated not washing hands to disease and people ignored

00:38:47.200 --> 00:38:48.200
[Amit Varma]: him for decades.

00:38:48.200 --> 00:38:51.440
[Amit Varma]: And I think if I remember correctly, he died in a lunatic asylum eventually.

00:38:51.440 --> 00:38:53.000
[Amit Varma]: Something really sad like that.

00:38:53.000 --> 00:38:54.520
[Amit Varma]: And that eventually got figured out.

00:38:54.520 --> 00:38:58.440
[Amit Varma]: But that was also the reason that around that time, things like homeopathy and all that

00:38:58.440 --> 00:39:02.160
[Amit Varma]: alternative medicines became common, because at least they weren't harming people.

00:39:02.160 --> 00:39:04.680
[Amit Varma]: I mean, of course, there is harm in terms of the opportunity cost.

00:39:04.680 --> 00:39:08.760
[Amit Varma]: You don't get some other treatment if you take sugar pills, but they weren't harming

00:39:08.760 --> 00:39:09.760
[Amit Varma]: people.

00:39:09.760 --> 00:39:14.080
[Amit Varma]: Whereas if you went to a hospital, your chances of dying were insanely high because evidence

00:39:14.080 --> 00:39:17.440
[Amit Varma]: based medicine, as it were, was simply not at that stage of advancement.

00:39:17.440 --> 00:39:19.360
[Amit Varma]: Now, that, of course, has changed.

00:39:19.360 --> 00:39:20.640
[Amit Varma]: And today it is.

00:39:20.640 --> 00:39:26.320
[Amit Varma]: But for most things, how important would you say these processes still are internalizing

00:39:26.320 --> 00:39:29.680
[Amit Varma]: them and with the washing of hands being the most basic example.

00:39:29.680 --> 00:39:34.200
[Amit Varma]: But if you think of do no harm, just kind of internalizing them and going with that,

00:39:34.200 --> 00:39:37.440
[Amit Varma]: I mean, there's a great quote, I forget by whom some famous doctor you might know.

00:39:37.440 --> 00:39:39.760
[Amit Varma]: I just read this recently on Twitter.

00:39:39.760 --> 00:39:44.120
[Amit Varma]: I think Anirban Mahapatra quoted this person in his episode with me on COVID-19, where

00:39:44.120 --> 00:39:47.400
[Amit Varma]: he said that at its core, every medicine is a poison.

00:39:47.400 --> 00:39:54.120
[Amit Varma]: So to what extent does the do no harm imperative of the physician go in both in terms of processes

00:39:54.120 --> 00:39:58.760
[Amit Varma]: or best practices like washing hands and all of that, and also just being aware that listen,

00:39:58.760 --> 00:40:03.080
[Amit Varma]: I'm expected to give a cocktail of medicines to this person, but all of them have side

00:40:03.080 --> 00:40:06.160
[Amit Varma]: effects, all of them can do harm in different ways.

00:40:06.160 --> 00:40:08.400
[Amit Varma]: Like we are finding out and we'll discuss COVID-19 later.

00:40:08.400 --> 00:40:12.760
[Amit Varma]: But if you give steroids too early, that depresses the immune system and chances are your fever

00:40:12.760 --> 00:40:13.760
[Amit Varma]: will go down.

00:40:13.760 --> 00:40:17.860
[Amit Varma]: But COVID will hit you really hard after that happens, which has happened in so many cases.

00:40:17.860 --> 00:40:23.200
[Amit Varma]: So how much of a part is just being aware of what not to do as much as what to do?

00:40:23.200 --> 00:40:27.200
[Guest]: I think it's extremely important to not trivialize any medicine.

00:40:27.200 --> 00:40:32.200
[Guest]: You know, for some reason, we have this concept of safe medicines and unsafe medicines.

00:40:32.200 --> 00:40:34.120
[Guest]: And what you said is absolutely right.

00:40:34.120 --> 00:40:36.240
[Guest]: It's the dose that determines what a poison is.

00:40:36.240 --> 00:40:39.440
[Guest]: I think there's a Latin quote which says that.

00:40:39.440 --> 00:40:43.000
[Guest]: You know, things like vitamin D, for example, you can overdose on vitamin D when given as

00:40:43.000 --> 00:40:44.000
[Guest]: an injection.

00:40:44.000 --> 00:40:48.280
[Guest]: And we've seen patients get admitted with hypervitaminosis D, which is a real thing.

00:40:48.280 --> 00:40:51.860
[Guest]: You know, it causes confusion, it causes a lot of problems.

00:40:51.860 --> 00:40:57.520
[Guest]: So even things which are seemingly innocuous may not necessarily be innocuous, may not

00:40:57.520 --> 00:40:59.920
[Guest]: be innocuous for a particular person, right?

00:40:59.920 --> 00:41:01.620
[Guest]: It may be okay for 99.

00:41:01.620 --> 00:41:02.620
[Guest]: So that's another aspect.

00:41:02.620 --> 00:41:04.640
[Guest]: Number one, it may not be innocuous for anyone.

00:41:04.640 --> 00:41:09.080
[Guest]: Number two, maybe what if there is a subset of people in whom it doesn't react well.

00:41:09.080 --> 00:41:14.080
[Guest]: And we just prescribe it assuming that, you know, these words which are used, you know,

00:41:14.080 --> 00:41:19.360
[Guest]: safe, vitamins, immunity boosters, you know, things that give a person a sense of something

00:41:19.360 --> 00:41:20.360
[Guest]: is being done.

00:41:20.360 --> 00:41:24.800
[Guest]: And because by virtue of something being done, I'm going to be in a better place than I was

00:41:24.800 --> 00:41:26.780
[Guest]: prior to receiving this.

00:41:26.780 --> 00:41:28.360
[Guest]: And yes, there is a placebo effect.

00:41:28.360 --> 00:41:31.300
[Guest]: You know, people do feel better with a lot of different things.

00:41:31.300 --> 00:41:35.680
[Guest]: And that is a challenge for a doctor as well, you know, in terms of, should I give something

00:41:35.680 --> 00:41:39.480
[Guest]: because that something will act like a placebo and make this person feel better.

00:41:39.480 --> 00:41:45.640
[Guest]: And therefore, you know, my obligation to be a caregiver of some sort should not supersede

00:41:45.640 --> 00:41:51.320
[Guest]: my obligation to just be absolutely right and proper about not unnecessarily prescribing

00:41:51.320 --> 00:41:52.320
[Guest]: things.

00:41:52.320 --> 00:41:53.520
[Guest]: So that's the balance that you have to find.

00:41:53.520 --> 00:41:57.720
[Guest]: So if somebody comes to me and somebody comes to another doctor, we're talking about a counterfactual,

00:41:57.720 --> 00:42:00.560
[Guest]: where the other doctor gives the patient a vitamin, the patient suddenly feels a boost

00:42:00.560 --> 00:42:05.960
[Guest]: of energy, he or she is happy, they go back feeling extremely satisfied versus the patient

00:42:05.960 --> 00:42:09.840
[Guest]: coming to me, I say, you know, you have nothing wrong with you, please go away, in the nicest

00:42:09.840 --> 00:42:11.240
[Guest]: way possible, of course.

00:42:11.240 --> 00:42:16.560
[Guest]: But you know, that person continues to suffer in some way, who's to say who's right in this

00:42:16.560 --> 00:42:17.560
[Guest]: circumstance, right?

00:42:17.560 --> 00:42:20.960
[Guest]: This is where the challenge lies, you know, the effect of placebos, should it really mean

00:42:20.960 --> 00:42:26.280
[Guest]: something to a doctor as well to give a placebo, but based on the fact that we are scientists

00:42:26.280 --> 00:42:32.000
[Guest]: and based on the fact that we hold on to science, for everything that we do, I think we shouldn't

00:42:32.000 --> 00:42:37.760
[Guest]: be doing anything without a strong rational reason or scientific basis that suggests that

00:42:37.760 --> 00:42:39.320
[Guest]: something is going to work.

00:42:39.320 --> 00:42:44.400
[Guest]: And you know, I'm equally passionate making this argument with tests, I mean, possibly

00:42:44.400 --> 00:42:46.860
[Guest]: even more than medicines, right?

00:42:46.860 --> 00:42:51.920
[Guest]: For me, if I order a test, the outcome of the test must influence my treatment decisions

00:42:51.920 --> 00:42:52.920
[Guest]: in some way.

00:42:52.920 --> 00:42:56.940
[Guest]: You know, if you look at probability, probabilistically, there was a study done, which shows that if

00:42:56.940 --> 00:43:00.360
[Guest]: you did eight random tests without a pretest probability, right?

00:43:00.360 --> 00:43:06.320
[Guest]: So not Bayesian, you just randomly just gave anybody eight tests, 20% of the population

00:43:06.320 --> 00:43:11.320
[Guest]: that you give those eight tests to would have one abnormal value completely by random chance,

00:43:11.320 --> 00:43:12.320
[Guest]: right?

00:43:12.320 --> 00:43:17.640
[Guest]: Now, if you increase that to 16 tests, I think it's about 16 or 20 tests, that probability

00:43:17.640 --> 00:43:19.140
[Guest]: goes up to about 99%.

00:43:19.140 --> 00:43:23.320
[Guest]: So one test will be abnormal completely by random chance.

00:43:23.320 --> 00:43:28.080
[Guest]: So if you've asked for a test, you need to know that if the abnormal value comes back,

00:43:28.080 --> 00:43:29.360
[Guest]: are you going to do something about it?

00:43:29.360 --> 00:43:32.920
[Guest]: And if the answer to that is, I'm not going to do anything about it, you have no business

00:43:32.920 --> 00:43:34.800
[Guest]: ordering that test to begin with.

00:43:34.800 --> 00:43:37.880
[Guest]: I think the same flavor holds true for medicines as well.

00:43:37.880 --> 00:43:43.280
[Guest]: You do not want to give medicines just because you can't leave a prescription blank, or you

00:43:43.280 --> 00:43:46.200
[Guest]: don't know what needs to be done.

00:43:46.200 --> 00:43:51.420
[Guest]: You give a medicine only when you believe that science has proven in some way that taking

00:43:51.420 --> 00:43:57.080
[Guest]: that medicine for that individual will improve his or her odds of getting better as compared

00:43:57.080 --> 00:43:58.080
[Guest]: to doing nothing.

00:43:58.080 --> 00:44:01.080
[Guest]: I think that should be the guiding light.

00:44:01.080 --> 00:44:05.880
[Amit Varma]: And earlier we spoke about doctors responding to incentives from patients in terms of overprescribing

00:44:05.880 --> 00:44:06.880
[Amit Varma]: and all that.

00:44:06.880 --> 00:44:09.720
[Amit Varma]: But doctors are also prey to other kinds of incentives.

00:44:09.720 --> 00:44:12.420
[Amit Varma]: And I'm told this is more of a problem in the north than here.

00:44:12.420 --> 00:44:16.680
[Amit Varma]: But I'd like your opinion on it, which is that, look, you're working for a hospital

00:44:16.680 --> 00:44:20.800
[Amit Varma]: in different places from whatever doctors will get a commission for every test that

00:44:20.800 --> 00:44:21.800
[Amit Varma]: they order.

00:44:21.800 --> 00:44:26.240
[Amit Varma]: So they incentivize to order tests, they get a revenue share in whatever their practice

00:44:26.240 --> 00:44:28.000
[Amit Varma]: brings in within the hospital.

00:44:28.000 --> 00:44:31.960
[Amit Varma]: So they are incentivized towards asking the patient to do maximum tests, which may be

00:44:31.960 --> 00:44:35.880
[Amit Varma]: unnecessary with, you know, all kinds of overtreatment.

00:44:35.880 --> 00:44:40.720
[Amit Varma]: And I know that just talking about these incentives makes doctors seem like heartless mercenary

00:44:40.720 --> 00:44:42.000
[Amit Varma]: beings.

00:44:42.000 --> 00:44:46.120
[Amit Varma]: And I don't want to give that impression at all, especially because what I think has become

00:44:46.120 --> 00:44:50.680
[Amit Varma]: visible to all of us in the last few months is that our frontline workers in the health

00:44:50.680 --> 00:44:54.840
[Amit Varma]: care systems, our doctors, our nurses, and other medical personnel are our heroes.

00:44:54.840 --> 00:44:57.200
[Amit Varma]: They are like the firefighters of 9-11.

00:44:57.200 --> 00:45:01.120
[Amit Varma]: How do you respond to these incentives and do these incentives exist?

00:45:01.120 --> 00:45:06.040
[Amit Varma]: How does someone like you then draw a line and say that, no, I'm not going to do this,

00:45:06.040 --> 00:45:08.160
[Amit Varma]: which would immediately hurt your income?

00:45:08.160 --> 00:45:10.080
[Guest]: How does one negotiate that?

00:45:10.080 --> 00:45:13.960
[Guest]: So I'm honestly fortunate to be in an ecosystem which does not demand any of that to me.

00:45:13.960 --> 00:45:18.160
[Guest]: So that makes me very comfortable in terms of what I'm doing.

00:45:18.160 --> 00:45:21.080
[Guest]: My hospital is an ethical hospital, there is no pressure.

00:45:21.080 --> 00:45:24.720
[Guest]: I can admit somebody, not give them anything and discharge them after five days, and there

00:45:24.720 --> 00:45:26.400
[Guest]: will be no questions asked.

00:45:26.400 --> 00:45:30.840
[Guest]: That being said, I have heard very often of these incentives being in place.

00:45:30.840 --> 00:45:35.440
[Guest]: But you know what I think, Amit, I don't think any doctor begins with a place that they would

00:45:35.440 --> 00:45:36.640
[Guest]: want to do that.

00:45:36.640 --> 00:45:42.520
[Guest]: I think every doctor possibly starts with a place that, listen, I will do what is indicated,

00:45:42.520 --> 00:45:45.080
[Guest]: I will do what's completely ethical.

00:45:45.080 --> 00:45:51.360
[Guest]: And if as part of doing something ethical, I get some sort of a bonus or some sort of

00:45:51.360 --> 00:45:53.680
[Guest]: kickback, what's so wrong in that?

00:45:53.680 --> 00:45:57.480
[Guest]: I think that's the starting point for people who indulge in that.

00:45:57.480 --> 00:46:02.360
[Guest]: The problem is, it starts off like that, but this is a line which is very difficult to

00:46:02.360 --> 00:46:03.360
[Guest]: walk on, right?

00:46:03.360 --> 00:46:08.800
[Guest]: I mean, like any other incentive in life, at what point does the incentive drive the

00:46:08.800 --> 00:46:13.880
[Guest]: prescription versus the incentive being incidental to the prescription is where the huge challenge

00:46:13.880 --> 00:46:14.880
[Guest]: lies.

00:46:14.880 --> 00:46:16.160
[Guest]: And this is true for anyone.

00:46:16.160 --> 00:46:21.520
[Guest]: So I mean, you know, I've worked with somebody called Dick Menzies at McGill, who would refuse

00:46:21.520 --> 00:46:24.120
[Guest]: to take a pen from a pharmaceutical company.

00:46:24.120 --> 00:46:29.120
[Guest]: He would say that the moment I have a pen from a pharmaceutical company, I will be obliged

00:46:29.120 --> 00:46:31.960
[Guest]: to do something nice in return to this person.

00:46:31.960 --> 00:46:35.960
[Guest]: You know, I've received pens from pharmaceutical companies, and I've never thought of it, because

00:46:35.960 --> 00:46:41.000
[Guest]: I believe genuinely that, you know, this is just a pen, this is not going to influence

00:46:41.000 --> 00:46:42.000
[Guest]: my practice.

00:46:42.000 --> 00:46:46.120
[Guest]: But to be honest, who knows, at a subconscious level, if that particular pen writes really

00:46:46.120 --> 00:46:51.040
[Guest]: well, maybe, or that particular pen is something that I'm very fond of.

00:46:51.040 --> 00:46:54.720
[Guest]: Maybe at a subconscious level, I will be more inclined to support that particular company

00:46:54.720 --> 00:46:56.080
[Guest]: which gave me that pen, you know.

00:46:56.080 --> 00:46:59.960
[Guest]: So I think these are inherent to the practice.

00:46:59.960 --> 00:47:04.280
[Guest]: I think the extreme version of it would be to completely not accept anything.

00:47:04.280 --> 00:47:09.520
[Guest]: But, you know, I think majority of us get into a zone where we honestly believe that,

00:47:09.520 --> 00:47:13.280
[Guest]: you know, a little bit here and a little bit there in terms of, you know, a gift for Diwali,

00:47:13.280 --> 00:47:16.000
[Guest]: for example, is not going to make so much of a difference.

00:47:16.000 --> 00:47:18.800
[Guest]: But that's a very tough, that's a very thin line, you know.

00:47:18.800 --> 00:47:23.400
[Guest]: And I think that's a challenge that most doctors face.

00:47:23.400 --> 00:47:25.040
[Amit Varma]: Is there a systemic issue here then?

00:47:25.040 --> 00:47:29.280
[Amit Varma]: Is there a systemic issue that, look, if you want to set up a hospital, you want to maximize

00:47:29.280 --> 00:47:32.760
[Amit Varma]: your revenue because it's obviously expensive to do so.

00:47:32.760 --> 00:47:36.400
[Amit Varma]: And this is one way of doing that, that you incentivize the doctors and then it just becomes

00:47:36.400 --> 00:47:37.760
[Amit Varma]: a vicious cycle.

00:47:37.760 --> 00:47:40.600
[Amit Varma]: And you've pointed out that your hospital, Hinduja Hospital, doesn't do this.

00:47:40.600 --> 00:47:42.760
[Amit Varma]: It's a quote-unquote ethical hospital.

00:47:42.760 --> 00:47:48.000
[Amit Varma]: So my question then is that, is it possible for new hospitals to come up that are ethical

00:47:48.000 --> 00:47:52.880
[Amit Varma]: hospitals or are they putting themselves at a competitive disadvantage with hospitals

00:47:52.880 --> 00:47:56.200
[Amit Varma]: that are unethical hospitals as it were?

00:47:56.200 --> 00:47:59.320
[Amit Varma]: I'm sure they wouldn't describe themselves that way.

00:47:59.320 --> 00:48:06.240
[Guest]: I can imagine that if healthcare is treated like the open market, I can imagine how not

00:48:06.240 --> 00:48:08.800
[Guest]: indulging in such practices would hit your bottom line.

00:48:08.800 --> 00:48:11.160
[Guest]: I mean, that's straightforward math.

00:48:11.160 --> 00:48:17.400
[Guest]: So I can imagine the fact that it's relatively difficult to compete and match up to maybe

00:48:17.400 --> 00:48:22.280
[Guest]: the incomes of other individuals in other hospitals if you don't play the game by the

00:48:22.280 --> 00:48:25.320
[Guest]: rules that have been established.

00:48:25.320 --> 00:48:28.680
[Guest]: So I can see how that could be a problem.

00:48:28.680 --> 00:48:34.000
[Guest]: And I think that problem arises when you start dealing with healthcare as you would deal

00:48:34.000 --> 00:48:36.120
[Guest]: with anything else in the free market.

00:48:36.120 --> 00:48:41.560
[Guest]: And that's the reason, that's the whole conversation around medical ethics, the whole conversation

00:48:41.560 --> 00:48:46.560
[Guest]: around why patients need to be protected, etc., comes from this whole asymmetry of knowledge

00:48:46.560 --> 00:48:50.520
[Guest]: between doctors and the persons deriving the services.

00:48:50.520 --> 00:48:55.040
[Guest]: You cannot treat it in the same way as you would treat any other open market, which is

00:48:55.040 --> 00:48:58.680
[Guest]: why all over the world there are safeguards in place to prevent things from happening.

00:48:58.680 --> 00:49:00.800
[Guest]: I think that's the bottom line.

00:49:00.800 --> 00:49:04.840
[Guest]: There needs to be something in place to prevent it from being a completely open market.

00:49:04.840 --> 00:49:07.080
[Guest]: There has to be some sort of regulation.

00:49:07.080 --> 00:49:11.520
[Guest]: For example, the same pharmaceutical companies, if you take an example, are completely not

00:49:11.520 --> 00:49:16.120
[Guest]: allowed to do a lot of the things in stricter countries that they are allowed to do in a

00:49:16.120 --> 00:49:17.600
[Guest]: country like India.

00:49:17.600 --> 00:49:18.760
[Guest]: And why has that happened?

00:49:18.760 --> 00:49:19.760
[Guest]: Because of the same reason.

00:49:19.760 --> 00:49:23.720
[Guest]: The government has realized at some point of time that if you let it open, if you let

00:49:23.720 --> 00:49:28.120
[Guest]: it work or function like a free market, it's going to be demand, supply, it's going to

00:49:28.120 --> 00:49:30.400
[Guest]: be the same kind of incentivized.

00:49:30.400 --> 00:49:33.320
[Guest]: It's going to be not necessarily in the consumer's best interest.

00:49:33.320 --> 00:49:37.040
[Guest]: It's going to be in the best interest of the players, you know, and that's why it needs

00:49:37.040 --> 00:49:38.880
[Amit Varma]: to be regularized.

00:49:38.880 --> 00:49:42.040
[Amit Varma]: I would imagine that, you know, the solution can also come from within the free market.

00:49:42.040 --> 00:49:46.120
[Amit Varma]: For example, if you had enough supply, if you had enough, if you had ease of entry and

00:49:46.120 --> 00:49:50.800
[Amit Varma]: enough hospitals and all that, then some of them would advertise that we are ethical hospitals

00:49:50.800 --> 00:49:55.360
[Amit Varma]: in these ways that, you know, no commissions are given to doctors on ordering tests or

00:49:55.360 --> 00:49:56.360
[Amit Varma]: blah, blah, blah.

00:49:56.360 --> 00:50:00.000
[Amit Varma]: And then that would also, you know, it would become a competitive advantage instead of

00:50:00.000 --> 00:50:03.000
[Amit Varma]: something that you do out of pure idealism.

00:50:03.000 --> 00:50:04.160
[Amit Varma]: So that is also possible.

00:50:04.160 --> 00:50:07.440
[Amit Varma]: But anyway, that's that's a whole different question.

00:50:07.440 --> 00:50:08.440
[Amit Varma]: Let's kind of get back.

00:50:08.440 --> 00:50:12.320
[Amit Varma]: I mean, I have a bunch of other general questions I'll also come to before we come to COVID.

00:50:12.320 --> 00:50:16.360
[Amit Varma]: But I want to now go back earlier in your personal journey, which we left when we took

00:50:16.360 --> 00:50:20.640
[Amit Varma]: all these digressions that, you know, you're doing medicine and you're doing MBBS and all

00:50:20.640 --> 00:50:22.060
[Amit Varma]: of that.

00:50:22.060 --> 00:50:23.840
[Amit Varma]: What does the journey from that look like?

00:50:23.840 --> 00:50:26.360
[Amit Varma]: Like, how do you choose what to specialize in?

00:50:26.360 --> 00:50:29.880
[Amit Varma]: You've specialized in respiratory diseases and so on.

00:50:29.880 --> 00:50:31.920
[Amit Varma]: You've also spoken a lot on tuberculosis.

00:50:31.920 --> 00:50:36.040
[Amit Varma]: I also want to talk to you about sleep because, you know, I watched a presentation of yours

00:50:36.040 --> 00:50:40.960
[Amit Varma]: on that on YouTube, and it was extremely enlightening in many TIL moments.

00:50:40.960 --> 00:50:44.000
[Amit Varma]: But before that, tell me a bit about your journey that how do you get interested in

00:50:44.000 --> 00:50:46.760
[Amit Varma]: these things as opposed to other things?

00:50:46.760 --> 00:50:51.840
[Amit Varma]: And then what prompts that next sort of step where it's not just that you've become a doctor,

00:50:51.840 --> 00:50:55.640
[Amit Varma]: but you're actually going and doing an MSc in McGill University as you did.

00:50:55.640 --> 00:50:58.960
[Amit Varma]: Tell me how you're evolving during these years.

00:50:58.960 --> 00:51:03.360
[Guest]: In terms of the choice of specialization, I think very early on, for most of us, if

00:51:03.360 --> 00:51:06.880
[Guest]: you speak to most doctors very early on somewhere in the at the end of the first or the second

00:51:06.880 --> 00:51:10.400
[Guest]: year, people kind of figure out whether they want to become surgeons or they want to become

00:51:10.400 --> 00:51:11.400
[Guest]: physicians.

00:51:11.400 --> 00:51:15.640
[Guest]: So I think that's and it's quite fascinating, actually, you know, in terms of personalities,

00:51:15.640 --> 00:51:20.200
[Guest]: in terms of, you know, what kind of individuals are drawn towards surgery, what kinds of individuals

00:51:20.200 --> 00:51:25.400
[Guest]: are drawn towards medicine, I'm sure it'll make an interesting study someday to do personality

00:51:25.400 --> 00:51:29.660
[Guest]: tests and figure out who's drawn to what, even in terms of subjects.

00:51:29.660 --> 00:51:32.880
[Guest]: In the first year, we have something called anatomy, physiology and biochemistry.

00:51:32.880 --> 00:51:36.840
[Guest]: And very often, the guys who love physiology, end up drifting towards being a physician,

00:51:36.840 --> 00:51:40.680
[Guest]: the guys who are hardcore into anatomy, end up drifting towards surgery.

00:51:40.680 --> 00:51:43.060
[Guest]: And that kind of plays out further down the course as well.

00:51:43.060 --> 00:51:46.680
[Guest]: So I think very early on, physiology is something that fascinated me.

00:51:46.680 --> 00:51:51.760
[Guest]: And it still does, you know, just just understanding mechanisms is mind blowing sometimes why something

00:51:51.760 --> 00:51:53.040
[Guest]: occurs.

00:51:53.040 --> 00:51:57.040
[Guest]: And I think if you really understand physiology, you really understand a lot of medicine, you

00:51:57.040 --> 00:52:01.840
[Guest]: don't, you don't need, you know, superlative knowledge in terms of medications and drugs,

00:52:01.840 --> 00:52:04.680
[Guest]: as long as you understand the basics of why what happens.

00:52:04.680 --> 00:52:08.920
[Guest]: So I love physiology, I had a distinction in physiology, it was one of my favorite subjects.

00:52:08.920 --> 00:52:12.400
[Guest]: And I think that pretty much decided that I was going to be a physician.

00:52:12.400 --> 00:52:14.000
[Guest]: I also am a lazy guy.

00:52:14.000 --> 00:52:18.280
[Guest]: So standing in one place for like six hours was was not for me.

00:52:18.280 --> 00:52:20.800
[Guest]: So that so that got decided early on.

00:52:20.800 --> 00:52:25.720
[Guest]: Now at the end of your MBBS, it's the same fight again, right, a whole big pool of really

00:52:25.720 --> 00:52:30.520
[Guest]: smart people, all of them trying to get into coveted fields.

00:52:30.520 --> 00:52:35.440
[Guest]: I think a decent chunk of us end up in fields that we get rather than the fields that we

00:52:35.440 --> 00:52:37.160
[Guest]: initially want.

00:52:37.160 --> 00:52:41.400
[Guest]: The good thing about medicine, though, is that if you really like questioning things,

00:52:41.400 --> 00:52:46.280
[Guest]: if you really get excited about the body, and you know, small processes here and there,

00:52:46.280 --> 00:52:50.960
[Guest]: really, no matter what you decide to become, and where you end up being, where you end

00:52:50.960 --> 00:52:53.880
[Guest]: up being can be equally fascinating, equally interesting.

00:52:53.880 --> 00:52:57.520
[Guest]: Because if you take a deep dive into any particular field, I think it can be fascinating.

00:52:57.520 --> 00:53:02.620
[Guest]: So in my last year, I mean, I was, I fully knew that I was going to become a physician.

00:53:02.620 --> 00:53:07.840
[Guest]: But I had this gynecology professor who was really, really passionate about teaching.

00:53:07.840 --> 00:53:12.680
[Guest]: And I was completely in love with the subject in terms of, you know, I eventually got a

00:53:12.680 --> 00:53:18.760
[Guest]: distinction in the subject, I would read, I would, you know, attend labor, you know,

00:53:18.760 --> 00:53:23.880
[Guest]: watch things happen, be really passionate about gynecology fully knowing fully well,

00:53:23.880 --> 00:53:26.380
[Guest]: that this is not what I was going to become.

00:53:26.380 --> 00:53:31.160
[Guest]: And I think that's the passion that a good teacher, you know, instills in you that teaches

00:53:31.160 --> 00:53:36.340
[Guest]: you things about a field that you may not even be interested in pursuing, but you realize

00:53:36.340 --> 00:53:37.600
[Guest]: is fascinating.

00:53:37.600 --> 00:53:41.560
[Guest]: So again, to come back to the question, I initially wanted to do internal medicine,

00:53:41.560 --> 00:53:47.520
[Guest]: that was a broader, you know, head to toe, get an idea of physiology, how everything

00:53:47.520 --> 00:53:52.000
[Guest]: works in terms of the body systems, and then, you know, possibly super specialize in something

00:53:52.000 --> 00:53:53.000
[Guest]: else eventually.

00:53:53.000 --> 00:53:56.960
[Guest]: But again, you know, I mean, as usual, I didn't get into the first field of choice, I got

00:53:56.960 --> 00:53:59.660
[Guest]: into respiratory medicine purely by chance.

00:53:59.660 --> 00:54:04.400
[Guest]: So I was doing a presentation, I was working at Hinduja, it was a job that I was doing

00:54:04.400 --> 00:54:11.320
[Guest]: post MBBS, I was doing a presentation and Dr. Udwadia, who was the chest physician at

00:54:11.320 --> 00:54:15.000
[Guest]: Hinduja walked in and listened to the presentation at the end of it, he came up to me and he

00:54:15.000 --> 00:54:17.920
[Guest]: said, you know, that was a great presentation, etc.

00:54:17.920 --> 00:54:20.640
[Guest]: And I interviewed for medicine, I didn't make it into medicine.

00:54:20.640 --> 00:54:22.440
[Guest]: And then the respiratory interviews were happening.

00:54:22.440 --> 00:54:25.920
[Guest]: And I interviewed and, and it just worked out, it just worked out because he remembered

00:54:25.920 --> 00:54:30.540
[Guest]: me from this random presentation, you know, so it was just, it was good fortune.

00:54:30.540 --> 00:54:34.120
[Guest]: That being said, you know, I mean, respiratory medicine is very hardcore to physiology, it's

00:54:34.120 --> 00:54:40.240
[Guest]: very hardcore to internal medicine, it's very central to other body systems as well.

00:54:40.240 --> 00:54:42.240
[Guest]: So I completely enjoyed my residency.

00:54:42.240 --> 00:54:45.480
[Guest]: So my residency was at Hinduja.

00:54:45.480 --> 00:54:50.680
[Guest]: And again, there is a general perception of public institutes being much better than private

00:54:50.680 --> 00:54:51.680
[Guest]: institutes.

00:54:51.680 --> 00:54:55.720
[Guest]: And, you know, so again, my first choice would have been a public institute had everything

00:54:55.720 --> 00:54:57.920
[Guest]: aligned the way it should have.

00:54:57.920 --> 00:55:00.720
[Guest]: But it didn't, I got into a private institute.

00:55:00.720 --> 00:55:04.120
[Guest]: But I must say, I mean, the kind of education that I got here for three years was was really

00:55:04.120 --> 00:55:08.400
[Guest]: defining in a lot of different ways, you know, we had Dr. Udwadia and Dr. Mahasur, both of

00:55:08.400 --> 00:55:12.240
[Guest]: them senior, both of them very good Dr. Mahasur, who was the head of department of KEM.

00:55:12.240 --> 00:55:17.120
[Guest]: So he came from a public institute, he had served most of his life in a public institute.

00:55:17.120 --> 00:55:21.320
[Guest]: And Dr. Udwadia, who was at the frontier of research, he was somebody who was very passionate

00:55:21.320 --> 00:55:22.320
[Guest]: about research.

00:55:22.320 --> 00:55:29.260
[Guest]: We did this study in 2010, we basically took 106 different practitioners were practicing

00:55:29.260 --> 00:55:30.400
[Guest]: in a slum of Mumbai.

00:55:30.400 --> 00:55:31.840
[Guest]: This was Dharavi.

00:55:31.840 --> 00:55:35.240
[Guest]: And we asked them to fill up a prescription for a person with a standard weight.

00:55:35.240 --> 00:55:39.480
[Guest]: So I think we said the weight was 60 kilos, a person with 60 kilos came and sat in front

00:55:39.480 --> 00:55:41.920
[Guest]: of you and he has tuberculosis, write up a prescription.

00:55:41.920 --> 00:55:45.080
[Guest]: That was our that was kind of what we requested them to do.

00:55:45.080 --> 00:55:49.800
[Guest]: And 106 practitioners, if I remember right, wrote 64 different prescriptions, out of which

00:55:49.800 --> 00:55:54.340
[Guest]: six were what we consider to be accurate and right based on the current guidelines then.

00:55:54.340 --> 00:55:56.940
[Guest]: So six of 106 were accurate.

00:55:56.940 --> 00:56:01.560
[Guest]: So that was an eye opener as well, and that was when we realized it also opened my eyes

00:56:01.560 --> 00:56:07.080
[Guest]: in terms of tuberculosis and realizing that about 70% of the population, 70 to 80% of

00:56:07.080 --> 00:56:11.160
[Guest]: the population approached the private health care system first when they wanted treatment

00:56:11.160 --> 00:56:13.120
[Guest]: for tuberculosis.

00:56:13.120 --> 00:56:17.480
[Guest]: And most of our data, most of our information, most of our guidelines, everything was directed

00:56:17.480 --> 00:56:19.800
[Guest]: towards the public health care system.

00:56:19.800 --> 00:56:25.920
[Guest]: So it was this mismatch where everybody thinks about the private health care system as being

00:56:25.920 --> 00:56:30.360
[Guest]: driven by incentives, not being kosher in a lot of different ways.

00:56:30.360 --> 00:56:34.440
[Guest]: And yet, number one, you know, it seemed like patients were preferring us.

00:56:34.440 --> 00:56:38.480
[Guest]: And number two, there was this chaos in terms of prescriptions, in terms of the way medicine

00:56:38.480 --> 00:56:39.880
[Guest]: was practiced.

00:56:39.880 --> 00:56:43.600
[Guest]: So that was a big eye opener in terms of research, you know, that was that was the first major

00:56:43.600 --> 00:56:48.040
[Guest]: publication that I had, and you know, it got me passionate about TB.

00:56:48.040 --> 00:56:51.600
[Guest]: The other side, of course, was Dr. Mahasur, who taught me some really great things in

00:56:51.600 --> 00:56:54.000
[Guest]: terms of how to take care of patients.

00:56:54.000 --> 00:56:57.640
[Guest]: So Dr. Mahasur would insist, you know, we would go on rounds and, you know, I would

00:56:57.640 --> 00:57:01.560
[Guest]: start saying, 31-year-old patient who's this, this, this, and you would suddenly stop you

00:57:01.560 --> 00:57:03.920
[Guest]: and say, what's the name of the patient?

00:57:03.920 --> 00:57:07.200
[Guest]: And then all of a sudden, you'd realize that you were caught in the back foot, you didn't

00:57:07.200 --> 00:57:11.480
[Guest]: know the name of the patient, because, you know, everything was just details, right?

00:57:11.480 --> 00:57:13.800
[Guest]: You're taught to be detail oriented.

00:57:13.800 --> 00:57:17.920
[Guest]: And he was very insistent that we knew every patient by name, we knew a little more about

00:57:17.920 --> 00:57:21.760
[Guest]: them in terms of their background, we knew what their social circumstances were.

00:57:21.760 --> 00:57:23.560
[Guest]: And I think that was fantastic.

00:57:23.560 --> 00:57:24.560
[Guest]: That was an eye opener.

00:57:24.560 --> 00:57:30.000
[Guest]: I remember a situation where we had this elderly lady who was admitted forever, you know, one

00:57:30.000 --> 00:57:34.000
[Guest]: of those patients was not getting discharged, and Dr. Mahasur would come on rounds.

00:57:34.000 --> 00:57:36.040
[Guest]: And we would pretty much not do anything.

00:57:36.040 --> 00:57:39.680
[Guest]: So you know, as residents, you want to have as less work as possible, or you want to be

00:57:39.680 --> 00:57:40.680
[Guest]: streamlined.

00:57:40.680 --> 00:57:44.040
[Guest]: And we would constantly wonder, you know, why is this lady there, we're not doing anything

00:57:44.040 --> 00:57:45.280
[Guest]: for her.

00:57:45.280 --> 00:57:49.720
[Guest]: And then one fine day, he told us about the story about how she had problems at home and

00:57:49.720 --> 00:57:54.360
[Guest]: how she wasn't accepted at home, and how she didn't have a caregiver at home, and the moment

00:57:54.360 --> 00:57:58.120
[Guest]: she went home, she would deteriorate, things wouldn't work out for her, because there was

00:57:58.120 --> 00:58:00.160
[Guest]: nobody to take care of her.

00:58:00.160 --> 00:58:04.800
[Guest]: And he pretty much knew everything about the family, you know, which we, despite the fact

00:58:04.800 --> 00:58:09.760
[Guest]: that we spent every single day with her, hadn't bothered asking her about at all.

00:58:09.760 --> 00:58:14.380
[Guest]: So I think this balance was great, you know, the balance of cutting edge, you know, trying

00:58:14.380 --> 00:58:19.840
[Guest]: to identify the big questions in research, trying to really work on changing the world

00:58:19.840 --> 00:58:24.360
[Guest]: in some ways, while at the same time being completely grounded to the reality that at

00:58:24.360 --> 00:58:28.320
[Guest]: the end of the day, you know, we are caregivers at the end of the day, you can be all evidence

00:58:28.320 --> 00:58:33.000
[Guest]: based medicine if you want, but if you don't provide comfort to patients in some way, you're

00:58:33.000 --> 00:58:35.120
[Guest]: not necessarily a good doctor.

00:58:35.120 --> 00:58:39.520
[Guest]: So I think that made a big difference in terms of my training as far as respiratory medicine

00:58:39.520 --> 00:58:40.520
[Amit Varma]: goes.

00:58:40.520 --> 00:58:45.600
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, so, you know, in my episode with Karthik on healthcare, we'd kind of discussed a bunch

00:58:45.600 --> 00:58:46.600
[Amit Varma]: of studies.

00:58:46.600 --> 00:58:50.120
[Amit Varma]: And what they all showed is pretty much what you're pointing out about only six doctors

00:58:50.120 --> 00:58:53.000
[Amit Varma]: out of hundred and whatever, kind of getting it right.

00:58:53.000 --> 00:58:56.880
[Amit Varma]: And that was true in his studies for both public and private, in fact, public fared

00:58:56.880 --> 00:58:57.920
[Amit Varma]: a bit worse.

00:58:57.920 --> 00:59:03.120
[Amit Varma]: But my question before we move on is, why did the guys who got it wrong, get it wrong?

00:59:03.120 --> 00:59:04.860
[Guest]: That's a difficult question, honestly.

00:59:04.860 --> 00:59:12.440
[Guest]: So I think part of that is the fact that people just don't bother updating themselves sometimes.

00:59:12.440 --> 00:59:18.240
[Guest]: So maybe they weren't up to speed in terms of what the data was telling them, what the

00:59:18.240 --> 00:59:20.480
[Guest]: guidelines were telling them.

00:59:20.480 --> 00:59:24.800
[Guest]: Maybe nobody reached them in a way because they were practicing in a place where, you

00:59:24.800 --> 00:59:27.840
[Guest]: know, the dissemination of knowledge wasn't a priority.

00:59:27.840 --> 00:59:31.860
[Guest]: It was also a disease like tuberculosis, where drugs don't tend to be very expensive.

00:59:31.860 --> 00:59:36.240
[Guest]: So pharmaceutical representatives are not coming after you, telling you what you should

00:59:36.240 --> 00:59:40.900
[Guest]: prescribe and why you should prescribe it because it's not worth their time or effort.

00:59:40.900 --> 00:59:45.160
[Guest]: And I think a part of it is maybe a lot of them just had standard prescriptions.

00:59:45.160 --> 00:59:50.360
[Guest]: A lot of TB prescriptions are supposed to be tailored to a person's weight.

00:59:50.360 --> 00:59:55.000
[Guest]: And maybe they've just been used to prescribing a certain thing and just having a standard

00:59:55.000 --> 00:59:59.620
[Guest]: copy paste prescription for everybody that it just made their lives easier with the volumes

00:59:59.620 --> 01:00:01.260
[Guest]: of people they were dealing with.

01:00:01.260 --> 01:00:04.060
[Guest]: Maybe that was one of the reasons why that happened.

01:00:04.060 --> 01:00:08.680
[Amit Varma]: What also strikes me out of what your wonderful answer a while back was that the study of

01:00:08.680 --> 01:00:11.920
[Amit Varma]: medicine can take you in two opposite directions.

01:00:11.920 --> 01:00:15.680
[Amit Varma]: That on the one hand, it can make a person in front of you less human because you're

01:00:15.680 --> 01:00:17.000
[Amit Varma]: just noting down the details.

01:00:17.000 --> 01:00:19.280
[Amit Varma]: This is the age, this is the weight, blah, blah, blah.

01:00:19.280 --> 01:00:20.800
[Amit Varma]: And that's something you need to watch out for.

01:00:20.800 --> 01:00:24.280
[Amit Varma]: And as you said, you were fortunate to have a doctor who, you know, made you cognizant

01:00:24.280 --> 01:00:25.840
[Amit Varma]: and mindful of these things.

01:00:25.840 --> 01:00:30.800
[Amit Varma]: But on the other hand, it can also make them more human in the sense that we look at ourselves

01:00:30.800 --> 01:00:34.120
[Amit Varma]: and the people all around us as if everybody's immortal.

01:00:34.120 --> 01:00:37.260
[Amit Varma]: You know, we don't consider our own mortality.

01:00:37.260 --> 01:00:39.760
[Amit Varma]: And we even take others for granted for that reason.

01:00:39.760 --> 01:00:44.600
[Amit Varma]: But I'm guessing that once you start studying medicine, and it becomes explicit to you that

01:00:44.600 --> 01:00:49.320
[Amit Varma]: this is a body and this is how the body functions, and eventually it kind of breaks down.

01:00:49.320 --> 01:00:54.420
[Amit Varma]: Does that then change the way that you look at others that that veneer of immortality

01:00:54.420 --> 01:00:55.420
[Amit Varma]: goes down?

01:00:55.420 --> 01:00:59.120
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, you might, for example, go to a wedding and your aunt will complain about

01:00:59.120 --> 01:01:01.000
[Amit Varma]: how your uncle is snoring so much.

01:01:01.000 --> 01:01:03.960
[Amit Varma]: At an earlier date, that is just an endearing detail.

01:01:03.960 --> 01:01:07.720
[Amit Varma]: But suddenly you are now asking your uncle about his throat muscles, his uvula, does

01:01:07.720 --> 01:01:09.360
[Amit Varma]: he sleep on his side or not?

01:01:09.360 --> 01:01:12.360
[Amit Varma]: You know, any thoughts on these two, like very different aspects?

01:01:12.360 --> 01:01:15.640
[Amit Varma]: You've already commented on the first one where you have to be mindful and treat them

01:01:15.640 --> 01:01:17.080
[Amit Varma]: as actual people.

01:01:17.080 --> 01:01:21.560
[Amit Varma]: But the other one, does it does it kind of change the way that you look at others and

01:01:21.560 --> 01:01:25.760
[Amit Varma]: yourself and your own body that there are things that you would otherwise take for granted

01:01:25.760 --> 01:01:29.920
[Amit Varma]: and you see others take for granted, but you don't anymore because you know enough of the

01:01:29.920 --> 01:01:33.560
[Amit Varma]: body to know that this is stuff I need to kind of focus on.

01:01:33.560 --> 01:01:39.760
[Guest]: So that's the unfortunate part at a certain level, because you look at everything probabilistically,

01:01:39.760 --> 01:01:40.760
[Guest]: right?

01:01:40.760 --> 01:01:43.600
[Guest]: You start analyzing everything around you in terms of probabilities.

01:01:43.600 --> 01:01:49.080
[Guest]: So if you know that your loved one has a particular disease, you're already calculating probabilities

01:01:49.080 --> 01:01:54.240
[Guest]: of hospitalization, probabilities of bad outcomes, probabilities of what might happen.

01:01:54.240 --> 01:01:58.000
[Guest]: So you're also a party pooper right at the end of the day, like you rightly pointed out,

01:01:58.000 --> 01:02:02.120
[Guest]: you point out things to people who were blissfully unaware of some things and were living a happy

01:02:02.120 --> 01:02:06.200
[Guest]: life and now suddenly you've added to the problems on their plate.

01:02:06.200 --> 01:02:12.400
[Guest]: And that's a fine balance sometimes because I run a smoking cessation clinic, for example.

01:02:12.400 --> 01:02:17.360
[Guest]: Now you know a lot of people who smoke clearly know that it's not good for them.

01:02:17.360 --> 01:02:21.720
[Guest]: So you know, catching hold of someone and pointing out the obvious to them is not necessarily

01:02:21.720 --> 01:02:23.600
[Guest]: in their best interest.

01:02:23.600 --> 01:02:27.000
[Guest]: But you end up nudging people in the right direction, yes, you know, because you're more

01:02:27.000 --> 01:02:32.040
[Guest]: sensitized to the fact that, you know, what you are seeing cannot be unseen.

01:02:32.040 --> 01:02:36.200
[Guest]: So if you're seeing an individual who clearly, like you said, has a neck, which is bulky,

01:02:36.200 --> 01:02:41.360
[Guest]: fits into a certain profile, you know, you're almost tempted to ask, okay, do you snore?

01:02:41.360 --> 01:02:46.320
[Guest]: You go down an inquisitive pathway, but I think that has to be done with a lot of sensitivity

01:02:46.320 --> 01:02:47.320
[Guest]: as well.

01:02:47.320 --> 01:02:49.560
[Guest]: You know, that's the other thing about life, right?

01:02:49.560 --> 01:02:53.560
[Guest]: There is what we call the natural history of disease.

01:02:53.560 --> 01:02:57.560
[Guest]: So not everybody with a particular condition is necessarily going to deteriorate.

01:02:57.560 --> 01:03:01.420
[Guest]: Not everybody is going to follow a particular trajectory.

01:03:01.420 --> 01:03:06.080
[Guest]: So when you're actually eyeballing somebody and screening them, you're in effect doing

01:03:06.080 --> 01:03:07.720
[Guest]: a screening test.

01:03:07.720 --> 01:03:11.920
[Guest]: And your screening tests are solid only if you know the natural history and you know

01:03:11.920 --> 01:03:14.440
[Guest]: that intervening is going to make a difference.

01:03:14.440 --> 01:03:19.560
[Guest]: So when I tend to do that, I need to be reasonably certain that I'm giving advice that is going

01:03:19.560 --> 01:03:22.520
[Guest]: to possibly alter the trajectory of an individual's life.

01:03:22.520 --> 01:03:26.080
[Guest]: Otherwise, it's a little tricky to get into those situations, right?

01:03:26.080 --> 01:03:30.200
[Amit Varma]: One of the things that you kind of also then have to do is confront the limits of medicine.

01:03:30.200 --> 01:03:33.160
[Amit Varma]: Like the instinct, obviously, is I want to help the patient has come.

01:03:33.160 --> 01:03:36.080
[Amit Varma]: The patient also wants medicine, the patient expects treatment.

01:03:36.080 --> 01:03:39.640
[Amit Varma]: But sometimes you run into these natural limits where there's not much you can do.

01:03:39.640 --> 01:03:41.720
[Amit Varma]: The patient behavior has to change.

01:03:41.720 --> 01:03:44.000
[Amit Varma]: You have only so much control over that.

01:03:44.000 --> 01:03:49.160
[Amit Varma]: Like when I go to my GP, an endearing gentleman named Dr. Kothari in Lokhandwala, who has

01:03:49.160 --> 01:03:54.080
[Amit Varma]: I think 400 Ganesha idols in his office, a lovely gentleman, and one thing he will no

01:03:54.080 --> 01:03:59.480
[Amit Varma]: matter what I go to him with, he will tell me that, Amit, stop eating outside food, or

01:03:59.480 --> 01:04:03.840
[Amit Varma]: Amit, you must, you know, get enough sleep, both of which are true.

01:04:03.840 --> 01:04:07.720
[Amit Varma]: But there's a limit to how much control you have over somebody's behavior, which is one

01:04:07.720 --> 01:04:08.880
[Amit Varma]: of the limits of medicine.

01:04:08.880 --> 01:04:13.560
[Amit Varma]: And the other limit of medicine is that there are areas in which we simply haven't advanced

01:04:13.560 --> 01:04:14.560
[Amit Varma]: enough.

01:04:14.560 --> 01:04:19.360
[Amit Varma]: And with a particular disease that are advanced, you know, probabilistically, I mean, you can't

01:04:19.360 --> 01:04:23.480
[Amit Varma]: be cold and brutal and tell them that these are the probabilities, you know, at best five

01:04:23.480 --> 01:04:27.000
[Amit Varma]: years at worst six months, you know, that becomes difficult.

01:04:27.000 --> 01:04:31.400
[Amit Varma]: And sometimes there are diseases where, you know, maybe like GERD, for example, where

01:04:31.400 --> 01:04:35.000
[Amit Varma]: you can't cure the thing, it's just, you know, it is what it is.

01:04:35.000 --> 01:04:36.620
[Amit Varma]: So how does one deal with them?

01:04:36.620 --> 01:04:39.960
[Amit Varma]: Because a patient expectation always is of the doctor as a kind of a God who's got a

01:04:39.960 --> 01:04:43.480
[Amit Varma]: solution for everything, who better have a solution for everything.

01:04:43.480 --> 01:04:48.520
[Guest]: I think empathy plays a very important role in that situation where it's a shared journey,

01:04:48.520 --> 01:04:54.040
[Guest]: it's a shared experience, it's not didactic, it's not one way, it's nudging people in the

01:04:54.040 --> 01:04:55.040
[Guest]: right direction.

01:04:55.040 --> 01:04:59.000
[Guest]: And as you rightly pointed out, a lot of them have already connected the dots when it comes

01:04:59.000 --> 01:05:02.560
[Guest]: to lifestyle choices and lifestyle changes.

01:05:02.560 --> 01:05:06.840
[Guest]: I think it's useful to just nudge people in the right direction and offer them help wherever

01:05:06.840 --> 01:05:08.840
[Guest]: possible.

01:05:08.840 --> 01:05:12.260
[Guest]: Smoking cessation, for example, you know, there are medications which help, you know,

01:05:12.260 --> 01:05:14.220
[Guest]: and a lot of people aren't aware of these medications.

01:05:14.220 --> 01:05:18.340
[Guest]: So we tend to, you know, treat them as you would treat any other disease, there's no

01:05:18.340 --> 01:05:23.200
[Guest]: judgment involved, there's no, there's no, you know, point wagging a finger at the person

01:05:23.200 --> 01:05:24.840
[Guest]: and saying this is wrong.

01:05:24.840 --> 01:05:29.120
[Guest]: You accept the person for who they are, you try to help them to whatever extent.

01:05:29.120 --> 01:05:33.600
[Guest]: And then you also, you know, for diseases, as you rightly pointed out, you may not have

01:05:33.600 --> 01:05:34.600
[Guest]: a cure.

01:05:34.600 --> 01:05:36.760
[Guest]: So you be transparent in that process.

01:05:36.760 --> 01:05:42.400
[Guest]: I think it's important not to tell, you know, there is a school of medicine, which constantly

01:05:42.400 --> 01:05:44.000
[Guest]: reassures patients.

01:05:44.000 --> 01:05:48.640
[Guest]: I very often don't reassure patients in the sense that I say, listen, this is what we

01:05:48.640 --> 01:05:50.200
[Guest]: are going to try.

01:05:50.200 --> 01:05:51.840
[Guest]: It may or may not work.

01:05:51.840 --> 01:05:55.560
[Guest]: If it doesn't work, you know, we will try something else.

01:05:55.560 --> 01:05:59.200
[Guest]: I have very often offered patients to go and seek a second opinion.

01:05:59.200 --> 01:06:03.600
[Guest]: I say, listen, you know, maybe you should see another doctor, you know, maybe there

01:06:03.600 --> 01:06:07.040
[Guest]: are people who've dealt with this in a different way and have met with success.

01:06:07.040 --> 01:06:09.440
[Guest]: I don't claim to have all the answers.

01:06:09.440 --> 01:06:12.880
[Guest]: I think that's the kind of transparency that's really important.

01:06:12.880 --> 01:06:17.760
[Guest]: The other end of the spectrum, and you know, which gets me again, really disturbed is end

01:06:17.760 --> 01:06:18.760
[Guest]: of life care.

01:06:18.760 --> 01:06:23.480
[Guest]: Where very often I think it's the onus is on the doctor to kind of help the patient

01:06:23.480 --> 01:06:28.360
[Guest]: and tell them that listen, this is not a situation in which you need to prolong care, you know,

01:06:28.360 --> 01:06:31.280
[Guest]: you feel obliged to prolong care forever.

01:06:31.280 --> 01:06:35.240
[Guest]: And that's one thing that really riles me, gets me very disturbed when I see people,

01:06:35.240 --> 01:06:41.920
[Guest]: you know, who clearly are not doing well, who clearly are on multiple drugs, multiple

01:06:41.920 --> 01:06:42.920
[Guest]: supports.

01:06:42.920 --> 01:06:45.200
[Guest]: And you know, the family says just keep going on, keep going on.

01:06:45.200 --> 01:06:50.440
[Guest]: I think there's a huge responsibility on the physician to navigate that situation and help

01:06:50.440 --> 01:06:53.720
[Guest]: individuals realize this is not what you would want for yourself.

01:06:53.720 --> 01:06:57.940
[Guest]: So please don't subject somebody you love to what you're currently doing.

01:06:57.940 --> 01:06:59.080
[Guest]: And this is a common theme.

01:06:59.080 --> 01:07:03.640
[Guest]: I ask individuals, you know, who have their loved ones on ventilators and multiple supports,

01:07:03.640 --> 01:07:07.960
[Guest]: clearly not doing well, you know, I very often ask them, I said, would you want this for

01:07:07.960 --> 01:07:13.200
[Guest]: yourself 30 years from now or so, if you were in this situation?

01:07:13.200 --> 01:07:17.320
[Guest]: And very often the answer is a very absolute emphatic no.

01:07:17.320 --> 01:07:21.960
[Guest]: Then I asked them, would your loved one, you know, had you had this conversation with them

01:07:21.960 --> 01:07:25.160
[Guest]: 10 years ago and said, listen, 10 years from now, you will be in this situation, you will

01:07:25.160 --> 01:07:26.760
[Guest]: be on multiple supports.

01:07:26.760 --> 01:07:29.920
[Guest]: Would you want everything to be done at that point, or would you want us to let you go

01:07:29.920 --> 01:07:31.480
[Guest]: at that point?

01:07:31.480 --> 01:07:35.280
[Guest]: And they will say, you know, I know my dad, he would definitely not want to be in this

01:07:35.280 --> 01:07:36.400
[Guest]: situation.

01:07:36.400 --> 01:07:41.080
[Guest]: And yet we perpetuate this, you know, as you rightly said, you know, this is the same analogy

01:07:41.080 --> 01:07:43.040
[Guest]: of a disease that has no cure.

01:07:43.040 --> 01:07:47.560
[Guest]: There are certain situations where there is no hope, you know, or the hope is such that

01:07:47.560 --> 01:07:50.820
[Guest]: the person will never live a meaningful life again.

01:07:50.820 --> 01:07:55.560
[Guest]: And I think that's where a physician, the onus is really on us to help individuals make

01:07:55.560 --> 01:07:56.840
[Guest]: the right choice.

01:07:56.840 --> 01:08:01.040
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, there's a there's a great book by Atul Gawande called Being Mortal, which is just

01:08:01.040 --> 01:08:02.040
[Amit Varma]: about this.

01:08:02.040 --> 01:08:05.800
[Amit Varma]: And it also strikes me that, you know, one thing that people might not think about so

01:08:05.800 --> 01:08:09.640
[Amit Varma]: much, but I'm sure you have, and I'm sure doctors do, is that the responsibility is

01:08:09.640 --> 01:08:13.880
[Amit Varma]: not just to prolong life, but sometimes also to enhance quality of life.

01:08:13.880 --> 01:08:15.760
[Amit Varma]: And sometimes there is a trade off.

01:08:15.760 --> 01:08:20.040
[Amit Varma]: And what you, you know, must have faced is the difficult situation where you actually

01:08:20.040 --> 01:08:23.680
[Amit Varma]: have to tell a patient that, listen, stop the treatment.

01:08:23.680 --> 01:08:28.680
[Amit Varma]: What is that situation like, and also in all your years of practice, are there moments

01:08:28.680 --> 01:08:33.440
[Amit Varma]: which were difficult for you, that were really hard, that made you wonder that why am I putting

01:08:33.440 --> 01:08:34.440
[Amit Varma]: myself through this?

01:08:34.440 --> 01:08:38.440
[Amit Varma]: Like, I understand the gratification of helping so many people in small, small ways.

01:08:38.440 --> 01:08:43.040
[Amit Varma]: But there are also these painful moments where you can't help them anymore.

01:08:43.040 --> 01:08:44.560
[Amit Varma]: So how does one kind of deal with that?

01:08:44.560 --> 01:08:46.320
[Amit Varma]: Tell me a bit about it.

01:08:46.320 --> 01:08:49.760
[Guest]: So this to me is one of the most painful situations.

01:08:49.760 --> 01:08:53.880
[Guest]: And unfortunately, it's getting more and more frequent, having to deal with it, you know,

01:08:53.880 --> 01:08:59.680
[Guest]: where individuals have reached a point where they clearly are not going to recover, where

01:08:59.680 --> 01:09:05.560
[Guest]: they are on multiple supports, where life is just being prolonged, but there's no quality

01:09:05.560 --> 01:09:07.320
[Guest]: to that life at all.

01:09:07.320 --> 01:09:12.360
[Guest]: And yet modern medicine gives us this whole illusion of keeping a person alive, right?

01:09:12.360 --> 01:09:16.440
[Guest]: The word alive itself is very debatable in this context.

01:09:16.440 --> 01:09:18.360
[Guest]: I find this extremely difficult to do.

01:09:18.360 --> 01:09:24.280
[Guest]: You know, I was reading an article recently, the title of the article was How Doctors Die.

01:09:24.280 --> 01:09:28.080
[Guest]: And it was a very interesting article, which talks about how when doctors themselves get

01:09:28.080 --> 01:09:34.000
[Guest]: diagnosed with certain conditions, they choose to just go to a house somewhere in the wilderness,

01:09:34.000 --> 01:09:38.040
[Guest]: live quietly, spend the last six months, you know, with their family, have quality time

01:09:38.040 --> 01:09:43.280
[Guest]: and just pass away quietly, when they themselves have to deal with situations like that.

01:09:43.280 --> 01:09:48.240
[Guest]: And yet, you know, we offer a lot more to patients than we should.

01:09:48.240 --> 01:09:52.000
[Guest]: Now part of that is, of course, you know, that there is litigation that everybody is

01:09:52.000 --> 01:09:56.000
[Guest]: also afraid of, that how could you not do anything in a situation like this, which is

01:09:56.000 --> 01:10:00.480
[Guest]: why I think it's very important to have advanced directives, you know, legal advanced directives

01:10:00.480 --> 01:10:04.880
[Guest]: in place, if you've thought about it, and if you don't want to be subjected to something

01:10:04.880 --> 01:10:09.360
[Guest]: when you reach a point, but in the absence of an advanced directive, you know, most doctors

01:10:09.360 --> 01:10:13.280
[Guest]: will end up doing everything that the patient's family tells them to do.

01:10:13.280 --> 01:10:15.440
[Guest]: And I find this extremely difficult.

01:10:15.440 --> 01:10:21.120
[Guest]: So I've dealt with situations where there were individuals who were leading lives where

01:10:21.120 --> 01:10:26.520
[Guest]: they were almost non communicative for five and six years, you know, post after a stroke,

01:10:26.520 --> 01:10:30.980
[Guest]: but the loved ones would want to keep on going on, get them admitted frequently.

01:10:30.980 --> 01:10:36.480
[Guest]: So there's zero communication, there is no evidence of what we would normally perceive

01:10:36.480 --> 01:10:39.000
[Guest]: as being a living human being.

01:10:39.000 --> 01:10:44.700
[Guest]: And yet we would keep prolonging the situation just because, you know, the family has resources,

01:10:44.700 --> 01:10:48.320
[Guest]: the family has money, the family is ready to pay, you know, so who are you to question

01:10:48.320 --> 01:10:49.960
[Guest]: this decision.

01:10:49.960 --> 01:10:55.520
[Guest]: And one of the solutions offered in this article written by this doctor was that if you're

01:10:55.520 --> 01:10:59.800
[Guest]: uncomfortable with the situation, you need to transfer care to another physician.

01:10:59.800 --> 01:11:01.480
[Guest]: I've never I've never thought of doing that.

01:11:01.480 --> 01:11:04.080
[Guest]: But you know, after reading this article, it really made me wonder whether I should

01:11:04.080 --> 01:11:09.880
[Guest]: start doing that, because it goes against every belief that I believe in, it goes against

01:11:09.880 --> 01:11:10.880
[Guest]: my training.

01:11:10.880 --> 01:11:16.000
[Guest]: I train to become a doctor, not just to save lives, but to add some meaning to those lives

01:11:16.000 --> 01:11:19.120
[Guest]: to add some quality to those lives.

01:11:19.120 --> 01:11:24.840
[Guest]: And as you rightly said, you know, Atul Gawande's book talks about how, I think about 50% of

01:11:24.840 --> 01:11:29.840
[Guest]: your of your lifetime cost on medicine or medical care happens in the last one month

01:11:29.840 --> 01:11:31.340
[Guest]: of your life.

01:11:31.340 --> 01:11:37.080
[Guest]: So it's that stark, that just because we have the ability to put people on ventilators to

01:11:37.080 --> 01:11:41.920
[Guest]: start infusions and bring their blood pressure up to start dialysis and, you know, get their

01:11:41.920 --> 01:11:43.640
[Guest]: kidneys functioning.

01:11:43.640 --> 01:11:47.080
[Guest]: Just because we have this ability, we've started doing things which are which are possibly

01:11:47.080 --> 01:11:49.400
[Guest]: not always in the patient's best interest.

01:11:49.400 --> 01:11:50.400
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

01:11:50.400 --> 01:11:54.040
[Amit Varma]: And also, you know, within the culture, we might romanticize things like, you know, in

01:11:54.040 --> 01:11:57.760
[Amit Varma]: Dylan Thomas's famous words to rage, rage against the dying of the light.

01:11:57.760 --> 01:12:03.480
[Amit Varma]: Whereas I would certainly in that situation, just like to have the grace to just go quietly

01:12:03.480 --> 01:12:08.080
[Amit Varma]: and save everybody and myself the trouble, which, you know, brings me to euthanasia.

01:12:08.080 --> 01:12:09.680
[Amit Varma]: Like, what do you feel about euthanasia?

01:12:09.680 --> 01:12:13.440
[Amit Varma]: Like some countries have kind of moved towards legalizing it.

01:12:13.440 --> 01:12:16.040
[Amit Varma]: And for those who don't know, euthanasia is where at the end of your life, you choose

01:12:16.040 --> 01:12:21.920
[Amit Varma]: to just kind of go when you have a fatal disease or such like and and the two issues that the

01:12:21.920 --> 01:12:26.560
[Amit Varma]: two sort of related questions that come up is that in a country like India, you know,

01:12:26.560 --> 01:12:29.600
[Amit Varma]: where there is so much jogar and the rule of law doesn't really hold, if you were to

01:12:29.600 --> 01:12:34.240
[Amit Varma]: legalize it, you know, it could become a pretext for people to just, you know, murder their

01:12:34.240 --> 01:12:39.200
[Amit Varma]: older relatives and, you know, get the paperwork done to show that it's euthanasia.

01:12:39.200 --> 01:12:44.960
[Amit Varma]: But at the same time, if one agrees that euthanasia is a dignified way to end life and that we

01:12:44.960 --> 01:12:50.600
[Amit Varma]: should all have the right to end our lives, then what do we make of suicide in a general

01:12:50.600 --> 01:12:55.720
[Amit Varma]: sense that, you know, even if you're not ill, you know, suicide, of course, is criminalized

01:12:55.720 --> 01:12:59.640
[Amit Varma]: here, therefore becoming the one crime for which you get punished when you fail at it

01:12:59.640 --> 01:13:02.960
[Amit Varma]: and is often correlated with the mental health issues.

01:13:02.960 --> 01:13:05.720
[Amit Varma]: And there, of course, you know, it is something to worry about.

01:13:05.720 --> 01:13:11.320
[Amit Varma]: But at the same time, a completely cold, rational person might say that I'm not ill, but I just

01:13:11.320 --> 01:13:15.200
[Amit Varma]: don't want to go on and I have autonomy over my body.

01:13:15.200 --> 01:13:20.360
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, are these are these kind of questions that you've thought about?

01:13:20.360 --> 01:13:25.840
[Guest]: So I have, there's actually a very interesting documentary by The Economist, so, you know,

01:13:25.840 --> 01:13:30.560
[Guest]: Economist does these small documentaries about this Belgian girl who was 24 and chose to

01:13:30.560 --> 01:13:32.840
[Guest]: get euthanized.

01:13:32.840 --> 01:13:35.760
[Guest]: It's extremely disturbing, of course, to watch it as well.

01:13:35.760 --> 01:13:40.520
[Guest]: But, you know, medically, the dilemmas are, of course, whether it's active or it's passive.

01:13:40.520 --> 01:13:46.120
[Guest]: So active euthanasia is where a doctor plays a role in actually ending a person's life.

01:13:46.120 --> 01:13:51.280
[Guest]: And that goes against the oath that goes against the Hippocrates oath, where we are not supposed

01:13:51.280 --> 01:13:53.000
[Guest]: to actively help anyone die.

01:13:53.000 --> 01:13:56.240
[Guest]: That's that's not what our skill sets are designed to do.

01:13:56.240 --> 01:13:59.440
[Guest]: Then there's passive euthanasia, where you set it up for the patient, but the patient

01:13:59.440 --> 01:14:02.640
[Guest]: presses the button, the patient pulls the trigger, the patient figures out or the person

01:14:02.640 --> 01:14:07.600
[Guest]: let's not use the word patient figures out when the time is right and they want to go

01:14:07.600 --> 01:14:09.080
[Guest]: down that road.

01:14:09.080 --> 01:14:15.520
[Guest]: Now, the problem is that I absolutely agree with the autonomy part of things.

01:14:15.520 --> 01:14:18.080
[Guest]: And I think it's fair.

01:14:18.080 --> 01:14:21.720
[Guest]: I think it's better to go down that road when it's done as an advance directive and something

01:14:21.720 --> 01:14:27.640
[Guest]: is decided not when the time comes, which may cloud your ability to make a calm, rational

01:14:27.640 --> 01:14:29.600
[Guest]: decision, but it's done in advance.

01:14:29.600 --> 01:14:33.840
[Guest]: So I think advance directives are very nice in terms of saying, listen, if I reach a point

01:14:33.840 --> 01:14:38.400
[Guest]: where you have to do cardiopulmonary resuscitation on me, I don't want that being done.

01:14:38.400 --> 01:14:39.880
[Guest]: So the no code principle, right?

01:14:39.880 --> 01:14:42.400
[Guest]: People have bracelets which say that I don't want a code.

01:14:42.400 --> 01:14:47.280
[Guest]: I think that's relatively straightforward in terms of ethical frameworks.

01:14:47.280 --> 01:14:51.640
[Guest]: I think what's more challenging is what you just described, that you're not overtly suffering

01:14:51.640 --> 01:14:55.440
[Guest]: and yet you've decided that enough is enough and you want to go at your prime rather than

01:14:55.440 --> 01:14:58.360
[Guest]: go down a pathway where you suffer.

01:14:58.360 --> 01:14:59.840
[Guest]: I have thought of that.

01:14:59.840 --> 01:15:03.040
[Guest]: And I don't think there's an easy answer to that, unfortunately, because religion comes

01:15:03.040 --> 01:15:08.320
[Guest]: into play, personal beliefs come into play, the slippery slope, where do you draw the

01:15:08.320 --> 01:15:09.320
[Guest]: line?

01:15:09.320 --> 01:15:15.000
[Guest]: Is there a line at which you say it's okay to do it, and what is our role as a society

01:15:15.000 --> 01:15:20.920
[Guest]: in terms of protecting the individual from making a step that is so detrimental to them?

01:15:20.920 --> 01:15:25.120
[Guest]: Do we have some sort of an obligation to protect that individual in terms of counseling, in

01:15:25.120 --> 01:15:27.160
[Guest]: terms of going through a process?

01:15:27.160 --> 01:15:30.600
[Guest]: And to the best of my knowledge, the countries that do allow euthanasia also have certain

01:15:30.600 --> 01:15:34.760
[Guest]: measures in place where you need to go through a certain level of counseling, you need to

01:15:34.760 --> 01:15:39.600
[Guest]: go through psychiatric evaluation, everyone needs to be convinced that it's a rational

01:15:39.600 --> 01:15:40.600
[Guest]: decision.

01:15:40.600 --> 01:15:44.680
[Guest]: There is a situation which is irretrievable in some way, and only then you're allowed

01:15:44.680 --> 01:15:47.120
[Guest]: to go ahead with the decision.

01:15:47.120 --> 01:15:51.480
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, many, many fascinating ethical questions in play there.

01:15:51.480 --> 01:15:55.520
[Amit Varma]: Before we go in for a break, a question harking back to something that you said earlier, where

01:15:55.520 --> 01:16:01.320
[Amit Varma]: you spoke about how you'd like to see more of the humanities being taught in medicine.

01:16:01.320 --> 01:16:04.760
[Amit Varma]: And I completely get that because there is a danger that otherwise, you know, you could

01:16:04.760 --> 01:16:09.280
[Amit Varma]: just have a one track thing where you know how medicines interact with the body and that's

01:16:09.280 --> 01:16:10.280
[Amit Varma]: kind of it.

01:16:10.280 --> 01:16:14.580
[Amit Varma]: And obviously, it's more important to have a more well rounded approach towards humanity.

01:16:14.580 --> 01:16:18.920
[Amit Varma]: And also you spoke about, almost wistfully of the path, the road's not taken as it were

01:16:18.920 --> 01:16:22.600
[Amit Varma]: right at the start, where you spoke about one could have been an author or whatever.

01:16:22.600 --> 01:16:26.520
[Amit Varma]: Was there stuff like that in your mind at any point that were you interested, like what

01:16:26.520 --> 01:16:28.200
[Amit Varma]: kind of books did you read?

01:16:28.200 --> 01:16:32.920
[Amit Varma]: What were you outside the context of medicine and the study of medicine?

01:16:32.920 --> 01:16:33.920
[Amit Varma]: What were you reading?

01:16:33.920 --> 01:16:35.320
[Amit Varma]: Did you want to be a writer?

01:16:35.320 --> 01:16:39.360
[Amit Varma]: You know, when you read people like, say, Atul Gawande, or Abraham Verghese, or Eric

01:16:39.360 --> 01:16:44.040
[Amit Varma]: Topol, or whatever, do you think that, hey, okay, I should also be, you know, going down

01:16:44.040 --> 01:16:45.040
[Amit Varma]: that road?

01:16:45.040 --> 01:16:46.640
[Guest]: Tell me a bit about that.

01:16:46.640 --> 01:16:48.440
[Guest]: So it's definitely on the bucket list.

01:16:48.440 --> 01:16:53.840
[Guest]: And I do hope I will, I will write something someday of, of relevance and interest to to

01:16:53.840 --> 01:16:55.520
[Guest]: some readers, at least.

01:16:55.520 --> 01:16:59.600
[Guest]: I think a lot of my passion or my hunger for writing comes out in scientific literature

01:16:59.600 --> 01:17:00.600
[Guest]: and publications.

01:17:00.600 --> 01:17:04.840
[Guest]: And so that's, that's kind of an outlet in a way, the reason I could be a little prolific

01:17:04.840 --> 01:17:07.000
[Guest]: was because I really enjoyed writing.

01:17:07.000 --> 01:17:10.240
[Guest]: For me to construct something out of nothing is very fascinating.

01:17:10.240 --> 01:17:16.120
[Guest]: But this this concept of, of humanities also comes from how fascinating science is, right?

01:17:16.120 --> 01:17:21.600
[Guest]: So when I did my epidemiology, I realized that a lot of epidemiological principles actually

01:17:21.600 --> 01:17:25.400
[Guest]: came from economics, and a lot of them came from philosophy.

01:17:25.400 --> 01:17:28.840
[Guest]: If you look at, you know, we use something called p-value, right?

01:17:28.840 --> 01:17:32.600
[Guest]: So a p-value basically is a measure of statistical significance, right?

01:17:32.600 --> 01:17:37.400
[Guest]: So and when it's below a certain level, like 0.05 is a cutoff, we say that this, this is

01:17:37.400 --> 01:17:41.800
[Guest]: something that's rare, this is something that's, that that cannot happen by chance.

01:17:41.800 --> 01:17:44.080
[Guest]: So there is definitely a genuine association.

01:17:44.080 --> 01:17:48.560
[Guest]: So when you look at is drug A better than drug B, if the p-value is less than 0.05,

01:17:48.560 --> 01:17:50.120
[Guest]: you say yes, it's better.

01:17:50.120 --> 01:17:52.680
[Guest]: And it's beyond reasonable doubt or beyond beyond chance.

01:17:52.680 --> 01:17:58.440
[Guest]: Now, if you go back, the real argument comes from, from something Latin, which is reductio

01:17:58.440 --> 01:18:00.160
[Guest]: ab absurdum.

01:18:00.160 --> 01:18:05.360
[Guest]: You basically reduce the argument to a level that it's absurd that the alternative is true.

01:18:05.360 --> 01:18:07.160
[Guest]: And then you prove the truth accordingly.

01:18:07.160 --> 01:18:09.760
[Guest]: So that basically is coming from philosophy.

01:18:09.760 --> 01:18:14.880
[Guest]: And I think if we were trained in some sort of philosophy, in some sort of critical thinking,

01:18:14.880 --> 01:18:18.760
[Guest]: I think all of us would become much better doctors, because it wouldn't be that this

01:18:18.760 --> 01:18:21.360
[Guest]: is written in stone, we would learn to question things.

01:18:21.360 --> 01:18:24.400
[Guest]: We would learn context in a, in a lot of different ways.

01:18:24.400 --> 01:18:29.200
[Guest]: And this whole realization that, and when I say humanities, I don't necessarily mean

01:18:29.200 --> 01:18:34.200
[Guest]: the appreciation of art, I mean, things which actually eventually led to medicine in so

01:18:34.200 --> 01:18:35.640
[Guest]: many different ways.

01:18:35.640 --> 01:18:39.880
[Guest]: Abraham Verghese, to answer your second question, I think Abraham Verghese, My Own Country was

01:18:39.880 --> 01:18:43.760
[Guest]: one of my favorite books of all time, probably, because again, you know, it was the empathy

01:18:43.760 --> 01:18:49.680
[Guest]: that someone working at the start of the HIV pandemic in a small little town, the whole

01:18:49.680 --> 01:18:53.200
[Guest]: people coming out of the closet at that point of time, I think it was fascinating in terms

01:18:53.200 --> 01:18:57.760
[Guest]: of contextualizing medicine and not making it just cold, hard facts.

01:18:57.760 --> 01:19:01.520
[Guest]: Complications, again, by Gawande was a great, great book.

01:19:01.520 --> 01:19:06.080
[Guest]: His first book, you know, he's written some after that, which weren't as impressive, let's

01:19:06.080 --> 01:19:07.080
[Guest]: put it that way.

01:19:07.080 --> 01:19:09.200
[Guest]: But I thought Complications was, was fascinating.

01:19:09.200 --> 01:19:11.240
[Guest]: I pretty much read anything.

01:19:11.240 --> 01:19:14.000
[Guest]: I don't think I'm very selective about what I read.

01:19:14.000 --> 01:19:18.000
[Guest]: I think The Looming Tower was the last book that I can think of recently that I really

01:19:18.000 --> 01:19:19.000
[Guest]: liked.

01:19:19.000 --> 01:19:23.920
[Guest]: And then there's this book called Do No Harm by a guy called Henry Marsh, who's a neurosurgeon

01:19:23.920 --> 01:19:25.160
[Guest]: in the UK.

01:19:25.160 --> 01:19:26.440
[Guest]: And I thought it was a fantastic book.

01:19:26.440 --> 01:19:31.400
[Guest]: It's a book I read a couple of years ago, where he's so brutally honest about the mistakes

01:19:31.400 --> 01:19:32.440
[Guest]: that he's made.

01:19:32.440 --> 01:19:37.520
[Guest]: And he's so, and he can probably do it because he's relatively senior now, and you know,

01:19:37.520 --> 01:19:42.040
[Guest]: some of the stuff that he talks about would have potentially lawsuit material.

01:19:42.040 --> 01:19:47.040
[Guest]: But he's being so brutally honest about the uncertainties associated with medicine.

01:19:47.040 --> 01:19:48.040
[Guest]: And I find that fascinating.

01:19:48.040 --> 01:19:52.640
[Guest]: You know, I think, I think doctors need to be a lot more humble than they are.

01:19:52.640 --> 01:19:56.040
[Guest]: Because there is so much uncertainty there is on a daily basis.

01:19:56.040 --> 01:20:00.520
[Guest]: You know, I see patients in my clinic, I send them off home, there is a small proportion

01:20:00.520 --> 01:20:04.800
[Guest]: of those patients who anything can happen the moment they leave out of my office, right.

01:20:04.800 --> 01:20:09.320
[Guest]: And you know, that that uncertainty, I think quantifying that uncertainty and trying to

01:20:09.320 --> 01:20:14.600
[Guest]: become a better doctor, knowing that uncertainty is out there, is is what fascinates me.

01:20:14.600 --> 01:20:20.720
[Guest]: And I think, you know, it's a blend of philosophical, logical reasoning, it's a blend of accepting

01:20:20.720 --> 01:20:25.560
[Guest]: that uncertainty, it's a blend of this whole principle of do no harm, right.

01:20:25.560 --> 01:20:30.480
[Guest]: So the burden of proof is always on us to prove that things work.

01:20:30.480 --> 01:20:32.400
[Guest]: It's never on, you know, let's try something.

01:20:32.400 --> 01:20:36.560
[Guest]: If it doesn't work, then let's chuck it, because it's human lives that you're dealing with.

01:20:36.560 --> 01:20:40.640
[Guest]: And I think that structure of logic and argument also comes from the humanities, which I find

01:20:40.640 --> 01:20:41.640
[Guest]: very fascinating.

01:20:41.640 --> 01:20:46.760
[Amit Varma]: So I had a recent episode with another person who's been a voice of reason in these COVID

01:20:46.760 --> 01:20:48.520
[Amit Varma]: months, which is Gautam Menon.

01:20:48.520 --> 01:20:53.600
[Amit Varma]: And Gautam also spoke about bringing different lenses to bear, like, he brings a lens of

01:20:53.600 --> 01:20:56.200
[Amit Varma]: physics into biology and biology into physics.

01:20:56.200 --> 01:20:59.160
[Amit Varma]: And he's also got statistical training and all these lenses help.

01:20:59.160 --> 01:21:04.160
[Amit Varma]: So do you find yourself applying the lenses and the frames that you've got from your study

01:21:04.160 --> 01:21:06.480
[Amit Varma]: of medicine into the world at large?

01:21:06.480 --> 01:21:07.480
[Amit Varma]: And vice versa?

01:21:07.480 --> 01:21:09.360
[Amit Varma]: Like do you apply other frames?

01:21:09.360 --> 01:21:12.760
[Amit Varma]: Like one book that a lot of my guests seem to have liked and recommended on the show

01:21:12.760 --> 01:21:15.680
[Amit Varma]: is a book called The Rules of Contagion by Adam Kuczarski.

01:21:15.680 --> 01:21:19.280
[Amit Varma]: And there, of course, you realize that contagion is not just in the biological sense of how

01:21:19.280 --> 01:21:24.960
[Amit Varma]: a disease spreads, but similar rules and similar trends can apply to even, you know, contagion

01:21:24.960 --> 01:21:27.360
[Amit Varma]: when it comes to information, for example.

01:21:27.360 --> 01:21:32.800
[Amit Varma]: So do you find yourself doing this kind of interdisciplinary sort of applying of frames

01:21:32.800 --> 01:21:34.360
[Amit Varma]: of from one thing to another?

01:21:34.360 --> 01:21:38.360
[Amit Varma]: And then how much do you feel that that enriches your understanding?

01:21:38.360 --> 01:21:39.360
[Amit Varma]: No, absolutely.

01:21:39.360 --> 01:21:46.280
[Guest]: I mean, I can be pretty annoying to a lot of people sometimes because of this inherent

01:21:46.280 --> 01:21:48.680
[Guest]: cynicism that comes from epidemiology, right?

01:21:48.680 --> 01:21:52.440
[Guest]: So everything is in the realm of probability.

01:21:52.440 --> 01:21:54.040
[Guest]: So there's no certainty at all.

01:21:54.040 --> 01:21:56.040
[Guest]: Everything is like, what is the counterfactual?

01:21:56.040 --> 01:21:59.840
[Guest]: You know, what if this didn't happen and something else had happened is what you're trying to

01:21:59.840 --> 01:22:00.840
[Guest]: prove.

01:22:00.840 --> 01:22:04.080
[Guest]: And since you never have a counterfactual, you try to come as close to that counterfactual

01:22:04.080 --> 01:22:06.040
[Guest]: as you can.

01:22:06.040 --> 01:22:08.080
[Guest]: And that spills over to everything in life.

01:22:08.080 --> 01:22:11.960
[Guest]: So every time somebody is talking about, you know, say arranged marriage is better than

01:22:11.960 --> 01:22:16.480
[Guest]: love marriage, for example, and you're saying, you know, what the selection biases are, individuals

01:22:16.480 --> 01:22:20.560
[Guest]: who get into an arranged marriage is different from individuals who get into a love marriage.

01:22:20.560 --> 01:22:22.280
[Guest]: What are the confounding variables?

01:22:22.280 --> 01:22:27.120
[Guest]: You know, are they more wealthy and therefore have a safety net to go back to if they, you

01:22:27.120 --> 01:22:32.600
[Guest]: know, if it fails versus in one versus the other, and you're constantly dissecting it

01:22:32.600 --> 01:22:34.880
[Guest]: out in every aspect of your life.

01:22:34.880 --> 01:22:41.880
[Guest]: And I think that's the fun of the generalizability of the same principles across everything around

01:22:41.880 --> 01:22:42.880
[Guest]: you.

01:22:42.880 --> 01:22:45.360
[Guest]: There's this fascinating story, which I love telling, and you know, I'm going to use this

01:22:45.360 --> 01:22:48.280
[Guest]: opportunity to speak about it.

01:22:48.280 --> 01:22:52.880
[Guest]: There was this guy called Abraham Wald, and this was the Second World War.

01:22:52.880 --> 01:22:53.880
[Guest]: This was 1943.

01:22:53.880 --> 01:23:00.440
[Guest]: Abraham Wald was a biostatistician, was a statistician, and he was assigned to try and

01:23:00.440 --> 01:23:06.720
[Guest]: figure out why so many planes were getting shot down and, you know, how could those planes

01:23:06.720 --> 01:23:07.720
[Guest]: be reinforced?

01:23:07.720 --> 01:23:10.800
[Guest]: How could they make those weak spots stronger?

01:23:10.800 --> 01:23:14.000
[Guest]: He was given this data set where they had this whole bunch of planes and all the bullet

01:23:14.000 --> 01:23:16.280
[Guest]: holes on the planes were mapped on it.

01:23:16.280 --> 01:23:21.240
[Guest]: And he looked at all of them and, you know, it was clearly that the wings, the fuselage

01:23:21.240 --> 01:23:25.680
[Guest]: and the tails, you know, these were the three areas that were hit the most.

01:23:25.680 --> 01:23:29.440
[Guest]: And you know, as one would normally expect, the person would say, you know, reinforce

01:23:29.440 --> 01:23:32.480
[Guest]: the wings, the tails and the fuselage, because they hit the most.

01:23:32.480 --> 01:23:33.920
[Guest]: And what he said was just the opposite.

01:23:33.920 --> 01:23:40.400
[Guest]: He said, everything other than the wings, the fuselage and the tails needs to be reinforced,

01:23:40.400 --> 01:23:43.480
[Guest]: because these are the planes that came back to the base.

01:23:43.480 --> 01:23:47.320
[Guest]: The ones that were lost out were obviously hit in the other areas, you know.

01:23:47.320 --> 01:23:48.720
[Guest]: So that was his survivor bias.

01:23:48.720 --> 01:23:53.320
[Guest]: The ones that survived and came back, clearly did okay, despite all the bullet holes in

01:23:53.320 --> 01:23:54.320
[Guest]: all these areas.

01:23:54.320 --> 01:23:56.600
[Guest]: The ones that didn't were hit in the other areas.

01:23:56.600 --> 01:24:00.520
[Guest]: I think that's fascinating stuff and, you know, these principles apply to everything

01:24:00.520 --> 01:24:01.520
[Guest]: in life.

01:24:01.520 --> 01:24:04.680
[Guest]: If you just look at the data set, and you don't have the broader picture as to why that

01:24:04.680 --> 01:24:09.560
[Guest]: data is in front of you, and what's the context in which it is, you will end up making a lot

01:24:09.560 --> 01:24:12.080
[Guest]: of biased and flawed decisions.

01:24:12.080 --> 01:24:15.320
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, that's actually one of my favorite stories as well.

01:24:15.320 --> 01:24:19.720
[Amit Varma]: And Wald, in fact, served on a committee at one point in time with Milton Friedman and

01:24:19.720 --> 01:24:22.860
[Amit Varma]: a few other eminent people whose names I forget.

01:24:22.860 --> 01:24:27.360
[Amit Varma]: But I think Friedman once commented something to the effect of how it felt to be in a room

01:24:27.360 --> 01:24:31.320
[Amit Varma]: where everyone was smarter than you, which for someone like Friedman to say is pretty

01:24:31.320 --> 01:24:32.320
[Amit Varma]: remarkable.

01:24:32.320 --> 01:24:37.880
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, I think I get that feeling from the seen and the unseen as well, that

01:24:37.880 --> 01:24:42.240
[Amit Varma]: every week, I'm basically the second smartest person in the conversation, if there is only

01:24:42.240 --> 01:24:43.240
[Amit Varma]: one guest.

